<HL> Currency Markets: Pound Exceeds 3 Marks as U.K. Changes Tack --- Bank of England Halts Bid To Keep It at Key Level; Trend Depresses Dollar </HL>
<AUTHOR> Charles W. Stevens and Peter Torday (WSJ Staff) </AUTHOR>
<SO> </SO>
<CO> EUROP FREST CANDA JAPAN </CO>
<IN> MON FRX PCS CMD </IN>
<TEXT>
   The British pound surged in a powerful rally yesterday, as the <ORGANIZATION>Bank of England</ORGANIZATION> abandoned a long struggle to contain the currency's value in favor of a more anti-inflationary strategy. 

   The pound was quoted at <MONEY>$1.8182</MONEY> in late <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> trading yesterday, up <PERCENT>2.5%</PERCENT> from <MONEY>$1.7745</MONEY> <DATE>Friday</DATE>. 

   Traders attached more significance, however, to sterling's breakthrough above the 3.00-West German mark level. 
For more than a year, traders said, the British central bank had sought to keep the pound under <MONEY>3.00 marks</MONEY> through interest rate policies and foreign exchange market intervention. 

   Yesterday, the pound climbed <PERCENT>1.7%</PERCENT> to <MONEY>3.0488 marks</MONEY> in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>, compared with 2.9987 <DATE>Friday</DATE>. 
Traders said the <ORGANIZATION>Bank of England</ORGANIZATION> intervened in early European trading by selling sterling to depress its price but quickly dropped the effort. 
"It was a situation where the <ORGANIZATION>Bank of England</ORGANIZATION> finally threw in the towel. 
The pressure to push sterling through <MONEY>3 marks</MONEY> was irresistable," said <PERSON>Robert Hatcher</PERSON>, vice president and corporate foreign exchange dealer at <ORGANIZATION>Barclays Bank PLC</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>. 

   In midmorning trading in <LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION> <DATE>Tuesday</DATE>, the dollar was quoted at <MONEY>127.93 yen</MONEY>, down from <MONEY>128.87 yen</MONEY> <DATE>Monday</DATE>. 

   Economists interpreted the <ORGANIZATION>Bank of England</ORGANIZATION>'s willingness to let the pound rise above <MONEY>3 marks</MONEY> as signaling the higher priority the <LOCATION>U.K.</LOCATION> government places on fighting inflation over stimulating export growth. 
By keeping sterling's value down, the government encourages exports by making British goods less expensive for foreigners, particularly in <LOCATION>Europe</LOCATION>, to buy. 

   The <ORGANIZATION>Bank of England</ORGANIZATION>'s sales of sterling through intervention to contain the pound's value tended to be inflationary as they expanded the British money supply and put downward pressure on interest rates. 

   Moreover, containing sterling's value has become an increasingly difficult battle. 
Because of recent stability in dollar exchange rates and interest rate differentials favoring British investments, currency traders have been moving heavily into sterling. 

   "If you feel that exchange rates are going to be fairly stagnant, then you're going to go where you can earn high interest rates," <PERSON>James H. Hohorst</PERSON>, managing director of foreign exchange at <ORGANIZATION>Manufacturers Hanover Trust Co.</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>, said. 

   For more than a year the British government corraled the pound in a range between 2.93 and <MONEY>3.00 marks</MONEY>. 
Last week the <ORGANIZATION>Bank of England</ORGANIZATION> sold as much as <MONEY>3 billion pounds</MONEY> in currency market intervention to offset upward pressure. 
Market economists speculated yesterday that British monetary authorities may now try to keep the pound between 2.95 and <MONEY>3.10 marks</MONEY>. 
In <LOCATION>London</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>U.K.</LOCATION> officials declined to discuss limits it may have for sterling exchange rates. 

   U.K. officials stressed, however, that they haven't abandoned their goal of keeping the pound within a relatively narrow range. 

   The ease with which <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> appeared to raise its sterling target range yesterday is bound to strengthen the hand of Prime Minister <PERSON>Margaret Thatcher</PERSON> in resisting calls to join the <ORGANIZATION>European Monetary System</ORGANIZATION>, the eight-currency exchange rate mechanism. 
An <ORGANIZATION>EMS</ORGANIZATION> currency realignment, by contrast, usually involves complicated and time-consuming negotiations. 
<PERSON>Mrs. Thatcher</PERSON> contends the <ORGANIZATION>EMS</ORGANIZATION> is too inflexible. 

   The policy shift may lead to renewed dollar weakness, analysts predicted. 
The <ORGANIZATION>Bank of England</ORGANIZATION> has amassed <MONEY>$42.93 billion</MONEY> in foreign-currency reserves, almost half of it from buying dollars and selling sterling during the past year to support the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> currency and keep the pound stable. 
"One of the big (buyers) in dollars is out of the market now," said <PERSON>Brendan Brown</PERSON>, an economist with <ORGANIZATION>County Natwest</ORGANIZATION>, the investment banking arm of <ORGANIZATION>National Westminster Bank PLC</ORGANIZATION>. 

   On the <ORGANIZATION>Commodity Exchange</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>, gold for current delivery fell <MONEY>10 cents</MONEY> an ounce to <MONEY>$437.30</MONEY> in moderate trading. 
The estimated volume was 2.5 million ounces. 

   Gold was quoted at <MONEY>$437.10</MONEY> an ounce in early trading <DATE>Tuesday</DATE> in <LOCATION>Hong Kong</LOCATION>. 

