<HL> Currency Markets: Pound Extends Its Rise, Fueled By High Rates --- Dollar Is Mixed in Light Day As British Investments Offer Alluring Returns </HL>
<AUTHOR> Charles W. Stevens (WSJ Staff) </AUTHOR>
<SO> </SO>
<CO> EUROP JAPAN FREST CANDA </CO>
<IN> MON FRX PCS CMD </IN>
<TEXT>
   Relatively high interest rates continued to bolster the British pound in an otherwise sleepy foreign exchange market yesterday. 
The dollar was narrowly mixed against most major currencies. 

   "Sterling was the only mover in the Street," said <PERSON>Cynthia H. Johnson</PERSON>, vice president and corporate foreign exchange manager at <ORGANIZATION>Lloyds Bank PLC</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>. 
Interest rate differentials favoring British investments over those of other major industrial countries provided "a big incentive" to buy sterling, she said. 

   The pound was quoted at <MONEY>$1.7760</MONEY> in late <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> trading, up from <MONEY>$1.7740</MONEY> <DATE>Monday</DATE>, marking its ninth advance against the dollar in the past 11 trading days. 
The pound also strengthened against its European counterparts, climbing, for example, to 2.9970 West German marks from 2.9936. 

   If sterling's current trend continues, traders said a possible showdown looms between market forces and the <ORGANIZATION>Bank of England</ORGANIZATION> when the pound reaches the 3.00-mark level. 
Over the past year, the British central bank has consistently intervened in trading to prevent the pound from overtaking the 3.00-mark level by selling sterling in the market, depressing its price. 

   The British government is believed to be concerned that if sterling strengthened beyond that point, it would hurt exports to continental <LOCATION>Europe</LOCATION>. 
That would affect trade with <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION>'s primary trading partners, many of which have currencies pegged to the mark. 
These concerns were underscored <DATE>Monday</DATE> when the <LOCATION>U.K.</LOCATION> government disclosed a record trade deficit for <DATE>January</DATE>. 

   "The <ORGANIZATION>Bank of England</ORGANIZATION> has a lot of reserves, and they can, if they wish, hold (sterling) below 3.00" marks, <PERSON>Ms. Johnson</PERSON> said. 

   Traders believe <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> is less concerned about sterling's dollar value because the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> is a less significant trading partner. 

   Despite the threat of central bank resistance, many dealers find yields on sterling investments irresistible, especially while relatively stable exchange rates overall lessen opportunities for trading profits. 
"When you see the market quiet like this, money moves to high-interest rate currencies. 
If things are quiet, people are going to put money where they can earn interest," said <PERSON>Paul R. Loffredo</PERSON>, vice president and chief dealer at <ORGANIZATION>Security Pacific National Bank</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>. 

   Yields on closely watched, three-month Eurodeposits were <PERCENT>9.125%</PERCENT> for sterling investments, in contrast to <PERCENT>3.375%</PERCENT> for mark instruments and <PERCENT>6.75%</PERCENT> for dollar investments. 

   In other trading yesterday, the dollar was little changed. 
The <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> currency firmed to <MONEY>128.40 yen</MONEY>, from 128.25, and was unchanged at <MONEY>1.6875 marks</MONEY>. 

   In early trading in <LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION> <DATE>Wednesday</DATE>, the dollar was quoted at <MONEY>128.45 yen</MONEY>. 

   Statements by <ORGANIZATION>U.S. Treasury</ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON>James Baker</PERSON> that the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> and other nations will work toward stable exchange rates and that the federal budget deficit is under control failed to impress the currency market yesterday, traders said. 

   "Looking at rates now, they're not going to have to work very hard to achieve stability," one trader said. 

   <PERSON>Mr. Baker</PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION>Senate Appropriations Committee</ORGANIZATION> that a further decline in the dollar could be counterproductive and as a result, the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> and its major trading partners will work closely to foster exchange rate stability. 
"I want to assure you that the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> will do its part in this effort," he said. 

   On the <ORGANIZATION>Commodity Exchange</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>, gold for current delivery rose <MONEY>50 cents</MONEY> an ounce to <MONEY>$431</MONEY> in brisk trading. 
The estimated volume was 5.8 million ounces. 

   Gold was quoted at <MONEY>$431.50</MONEY> an ounce in early trading <DATE>Wednesday</DATE> in <LOCATION>Hong Kong</LOCATION>. 

