<HL> Currency Markets: Dealers to Focus on U.K. to Determine If It Will Attempt to Stem Pound's Rise </HL>
<AUTHOR> Michael R. Sesit and Peter Torday (WSJ Staff) </AUTHOR>
<SO> </SO>
<CO> EUROP FREST JAPAN CANDA </CO>
<IN> PCS CMD MON FRX </IN>
<TEXT>
   Profit-hungry currency traders this week will be focusing on the British government to see if it finally acts to keep a lid on its fast-rising currency. 

   The British pound already has climbed <PERCENT>5%</PERCENT> against the dollar and <PERCENT>2.8%</PERCENT> against the West German mark in the past seven trading days. 
So dealers and analysts are trying to guess at what point the British government will do something to stem the rise -- if, indeed, it does anything at all. 

   Meanwhile, <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION>'s economy is robust, its interest rates high, and the <ORGANIZATION>Bank of England</ORGANIZATION> appears to have abandoned intervention to hold sterling down. 
But last week also was marked by what appears to be a public conflict between Prime Minister <PERSON>Margaret Thatcher</PERSON> and her most senior <ORGANIZATION>Treasury</ORGANIZATION> official over exchange-rate policy. 

   In late <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> trading <DATE>Friday</DATE>, the pound advanced to <MONEY>$1.8565</MONEY> from <MONEY>$1.8460</MONEY> late <DATE>Thursday</DATE>. 

   Right now, the betting is that the British currency will get another shot in the arm tomorrow when Chancellor of the Exchequer <PERSON>Nigel Lawson</PERSON> delivers to parliament the government's budget for the fiscal year beginning in <DATE>April</DATE>. 

   <PERSON>Peter Fellner</PERSON>, a <LOCATION>U.K.</LOCATION> economist at <ORGANIZATION>James Capel &amp; Co.</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>London</LOCATION>, expects <PERSON>Mr. Lawson</PERSON>'s budget to show a surplus for the year in addition to as much as <MONEY>#4 billion</MONEY> (<MONEY>$7.4 billion</MONEY>) in tax cuts, particularly to the wealthy. 

   "The budget is likely to be very positive for the pound," says <PERSON>Gavyn Davies</PERSON>, chief <LOCATION>U.K.</LOCATION> economist for <ORGANIZATION>Goldman Sachs International Corp.</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>London</LOCATION>. 
Noting that <PERSON>Mr. Lawson</PERSON> has the opportunity to combine a fairly tight fiscal program with "supply-side cuts in marginal income-tax rates," he adds: "You can get the best bits of <PERSON>Reagan</PERSON>'s tax package without the worst bits of <PERSON>Reagan</PERSON>'s tax package." 

   As long as the tax cuts are modest and don't threaten the anticipated surplus, "there'll be no downside for sterling," predicts <PERSON>Paul Chertkow</PERSON>, director of economics at <ORGANIZATION>Security Pacific Hoare Govett</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>London</LOCATION>. 

   For more than a year, <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> maintained an unofficial policy of trying to hold the pound between 2.93 West German marks and <MONEY>3.00 marks</MONEY>. 
When the currency threatened to break above <MONEY>3.00 marks</MONEY>, the <ORGANIZATION>Bank of England</ORGANIZATION> resorted to intervention -- at times massively -- to keep the pound from rising. 

   The pound-mark rate -- and, thus, the other European currencies that effectively or actually are pegged to it -- are more important to <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> than the pound-dollar rate. 
That's because about <PERCENT>60%</PERCENT> of the <LOCATION>U.K.</LOCATION>'s exports go to <LOCATION>Europe</LOCATION> vs. <PERCENT>10%</PERCENT> to the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> 

   But <DATE>last week</DATE>, Prime Minister <PERSON>Thatcher</PERSON>'s opposition to any more large-scale currency intervention enabled the pound to break through the 3-mark ceiling. 
Having risen as high as <MONEY>3.0850 marks</MONEY> during the week, sterling stood at <MONEY>3.0818 marks</MONEY> late <DATE>Friday</DATE> in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>. 

   Twice last week, <PERSON>Mrs. Thatcher</PERSON> said that <LOCATION>London</LOCATION> wouldn't use either "excessive" intervention or lower interest rates to weaken its currency. 
She also argued that "there is no way to buck the market." 
<PERSON>Mrs. Thatcher</PERSON>'s prime motive is to battle inflationary pressures in the British economy, which economists say is expanding at <PERCENT>3%</PERCENT> a year in real terms with inflation currently at <PERCENT>3.3%</PERCENT> and expected to rise to <PERCENT>4%</PERCENT> at year end. 
Meanwhile, <LOCATION>West Germany</LOCATION>'s economy is growing at about half that pace with inflation at only <PERCENT>0.9%</PERCENT> a year. 

   <PERSON>Mrs. Thatcher</PERSON>'s stance has put her at odds with <PERSON>Mr. Lawson</PERSON>, who has advocated maintaining a tightly controlled course for sterling and <DATE>last week</DATE> contended that its advance was "unsustainable." 

   Moreover, senior <ORGANIZATION>British Treasury</ORGANIZATION> officials continue to insist that exchange-rate policy hadn't changed, and have asserted the government would use selective currency intervention and interest-rate changes to keep the pound stable. 

   So far, the market is skeptical. 
"<PERSON>Mr. 
Lawson</PERSON> can hardly stand up now and say we need fixity of exchange rates, <PERSON>Bretton Woods</PERSON> style," says <PERSON>Stephen Lewis</PERSON>, director of economic research at <LOCATION>London</LOCATION> stockbrokers <PERSON>Phillips</PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION>Drew</ORGANIZATION>, a unit of the <ORGANIZATION>Union Bank of Switzerland</ORGANIZATION>. 

   "At the moment we are in a sort of limbo period. 
No one knows what actually the policy is," adds <PERSON>Mr. Fellner</PERSON> of <PERSON>James Capel</PERSON>. 

   Nonetheless, many analysts suspect that the <ORGANIZATION>Bank of England</ORGANIZATION> has an upper limit in mind and predict that the market will force the issue by trying to push sterling still higher. 

   Many traders believe the first test of <LOCATION>London</LOCATION>'s intentions will be <MONEY>3.10 marks</MONEY> and come soon after the release of the budget. 
Currency dealers "will be tapping lightly at 3.10 to see if they can bring the <ORGANIZATION>Bank</ORGANIZATION> (of <LOCATION>England</LOCATION>) out," predicts <PERSON>Jeff Mondschein</PERSON>, a vice president at <ORGANIZATION>Merrill Lynch International</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>. 

   <PERSON>Mr. Davies</PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION>Goldman Sachs</ORGANIZATION> puts the threshhold a little higher. 
"They won't make much of an effort to stop a rise to <MONEY>3.15 marks</MONEY>; anything much above that and they will intervene," he says. 
Meanwhile, he sees sterling rising to at least <MONEY>$1.90</MONEY> to <MONEY>$2</MONEY> "quite soon." 

   Regardless, traders are nervous. 
Noting that the pound didn't climb to <MONEY>3.20 marks</MONEY> last week as some people had predicted, <PERSON>James Capel</PERSON>'s <PERSON>Mr. Fellner</PERSON> says: "Foreign exchange operators are sitting cautious; they don't know if the <ORGANIZATION>Bank of England</ORGANIZATION> is lurking around the corner to pounce." 

   ---
   <DATE>Friday</DATE>'s Currency Activity
   The dollar fell against most major foreign currencies <DATE>Friday</DATE> in what dealers said were quiet, nervous markets. 

   In late <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> activity, the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> currency stood at <MONEY>1.6600 marks</MONEY> and <MONEY>127.36 yen</MONEY>, down from <MONEY>1.6640 marks</MONEY> and <MONEY>128 yen</MONEY> late <DATE>Thursday</DATE>. 
Dealers said they were apprehensive that <DATE>Thursday</DATE>'s release of <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> trade data for <DATE>January</DATE> could be negative for the dollar. 

   In midmorning trading in <LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION> <DATE>Monday</DATE>, the dollar was quoted at <MONEY>127.20 yen</MONEY>. 

   On the <ORGANIZATION>Commodity Exchange</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> <DATE>Friday</DATE>, gold for current delivery settled at <MONEY>$441.30</MONEY> an ounce, down <MONEY>$1.90</MONEY> in moderate trading. 
Estimated volume was 3.5 million ounces. 

