<HL> Pound Rises,
U.S. Unit Gains
Against Others
---
By Charles W. Stevens
Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal</HL>
<DD> 03/05/87</DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO>
<IN> EUROP CANDA FREST JAPAN
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
PRECIOUS METALS, STONES, GOLD, SILVER (PCS)
COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD)
FOREIGN-EXCHANGE MARKETS (FRX) </IN>
<TEXT>
   The British pound resumed its rise yesterday, after having fallen the previous day on rumored intervention by the <ORGANIZATION>Bank of England</ORGANIZATION>. 

   The <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> dollar, meanwhile, gained against most other major currencies, despite its decline against sterling. 

   Despite the <ORGANIZATION>Bank of England</ORGANIZATION>'s apparent attempt <DATE>Tuesday</DATE> to thwart the recent rush of speculative money into the pound, dealers said sterling remains an attractive alternative to the usually more dominant market involving the dollar and the West German mark, which has shown little movement lately. 

   "With no action in the dollar-mark, the sterling cross is commanding attention," said a New York-based trader for a West German bank. 

   In the so-called cross rate between the pound and the mark, sterling yesterday climbed <PERCENT>0.9%</PERCENT>, to <MONEY>2.8818 marks</MONEY> in late <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> trading from 2.8558 <DATE>Tuesday</DATE>. 
Against the dollar, the pound firmed to <MONEY>$1.5644</MONEY> from <MONEY>$1.5610</MONEY>. 

   The relatively stable dollar-mark rate has decreased opportunities for making profits from trading those units, dealers said. 
That, in turn, has increased interest in sterling. 

   The relatively higher yields on sterling-denominated investments make the pound an attractive alternative. 
Optimism about a budget proposal due from <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION>'s government on <DATE>March 17</DATE> also continues to fuel sterling purchases. 
The budget is expected to include a tax cut and reduced government borrowing needs. 

   In <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>, <PERSON>William G. Orsini</PERSON>, corporate foreign-exchange manager for <ORGANIZATION>Bank of Montreal</ORGANIZATION>, said traders also believe that <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION>'s economic outlook justifies the pound's gains. 
He cited this year's surge on <LOCATION>London</LOCATION>'s stock exchange, in contrast to the decline in West German stock prices. 

   In other foreign-exchange activity yesterday, the dollar rose to <MONEY>1.8421 marks</MONEY> from 1.8295 and firmed to 153.76 Japanese yen from 153.56. 

   In early trading in <LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION> <DATE>Thursday</DATE> the dollar fell against the Japanese currency to <MONEY>153.70 yen</MONEY> from 153.76 in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> <TIME>yesterday afternoon</TIME>. 

   On the <ORGANIZATION>Commodity Exchange</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>, gold for <DATE>March</DATE> delivery climbed <MONEY>$3.20</MONEY> an ounce to <MONEY>$410.40</MONEY> in moderate trading. 
Volume was estimated at 3.5 million ounces. 

   Gold was quoted at <MONEY>$409.25</MONEY> an ounce in early trading <DATE>Thursday</DATE> in <LOCATION>Hong Kong</LOCATION>. 

