<HL> U.S. Currency Is Mixed, Sterling Gains;
Interbank Trading Spurs Wide Swings
---
By Charles W. Stevens
Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal</HL>
<DD> 03/12/87</DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO>
<IN> EUROP JAPAN FREST CANDA
FOREIGN-EXCHANGE MARKETS (FRX)
COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD)
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
PRECIOUS METALS, STONES, GOLD, SILVER (PCS) </IN>
<TEXT>
   The <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> dollar was narrowly mixed and the British pound stronger as both currencies seesawed in foreign-exchange trading yesterday. 

   Dealers attributed the wide swings to short-term speculative moves -- generated by interbank trading -- that didn't represent any change in the long-term outlook for either currency. 

   "It's basically the exchange market trading with itself," said <PERSON>James M. Pugh</PERSON>, vice president of corporate foreign exchange at <ORGANIZATION>Manufacturers Hanover Trust Co.</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>. 
"Corporate demand isn't there on either side." 

   The <ORGANIZATION>Bank of England</ORGANIZATION> was also rumored to have intervened in yesterday's trading, selling sterling at levels near the top of the currency's rise. 
Officials at the central bank and <ORGANIZATION>British Treasury</ORGANIZATION> declined to confirm the intervention rumors but reiterated that the government doesn't have specific exchange-rate targets for the pound. 

   The dollar's movement against the bellwether West German mark was the widest swing between those currencies in three weeks, traders said. 
The dollar traded as low as <MONEY>1.8538 marks</MONEY> in early European dealings and climbed to an intraday high of 1.8733 during brisk, midday trading in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>. 

   Expectations for the release of bullish <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> economic indicators, beginning with today's retail sales report, were partly responsible for the dollar's rise against the mark, traders said. 
But much of the move was purely on speculation, they added. 
"Buyers came out of the woodwork," <PERSON>Mr. Pugh</PERSON> said. 

   Then sellers followed, as speculators took profits on the dollar's rise, driving the currency back to <MONEY>1.8600 marks</MONEY> in late <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> trading, up slightly from 1.8565 <DATE>Tuesday</DATE>. 

   Trading in sterling followed a similar pattern. 
After trading as low as <MONEY>$1.5840</MONEY> early in <LOCATION>Europe</LOCATION>, the pound climbed to an intraday high of <MONEY>$1.6000</MONEY>, and then fell back. 
"It just got hammered," said <PERSON>Anthony J. Murphy</PERSON>, senior dealer at <ORGANIZATION>Royal Bank of Canada</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>. 
"I don't think it was a change in philosophy, just profit-taking." 

   In late <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> trading, the pound stood at <MONEY>$1.5933</MONEY>, up from <MONEY>$1.5865</MONEY>. 

   A trader for a British bank maintained that the <ORGANIZATION>Bank of England</ORGANIZATION> sold sterling yesterday to slow the momentum of the currency's rise. 
The pound has drawn attention recently as <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION>'s high interest rates have siphoned speculative capital from the comparatively stable market between dollars and marks. 

   Against the Japanese yen, the dollar eased to <MONEY>153.69 yen</MONEY> from 153.73. 

   On the <ORGANIZATION>Commodity Exchange</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>, gold for <DATE>March</DATE> delivery rose <MONEY>10 cents</MONEY> an ounce, to <MONEY>$406.90</MONEY>, in moderate trading. 
The estimated volume was 2.2 million ounces. 

   Gold was quoted at <MONEY>$407</MONEY> an ounce in early trading <DATE>Thursday</DATE> in <LOCATION>Hong Kong</LOCATION>. 

