FOREIGN-EXCHANGE MARKETS (FRX) </IN>
<TEXT>
   The <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> dollar eased against most other major currencies and sterling also weakened yesterday as rumors of central-bank intervention earlier this week tempered bullishness for both currencies. 

   The rumored intervention "took the steam out of the market . . . it just died," said <PERSON>Robert K. Ryan</PERSON>, vice president, foreign exchange at <ORGANIZATION>Irving Trust Co.</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>. 

   Meanwhile, the effect of yesterday's better-than-expected report that <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> retail sales climbed <PERCENT>4.1%</PERCENT> last month was offset by a downward revision of the <DATE>January</DATE> figure, to a <PERCENT>7.4%</PERCENT> decline from the <PERCENT>5.8%</PERCENT> drop originally reported. 
"The <DATE>February</DATE> number was great, but the revision was horrendous," <PERSON>Mr. Ryan</PERSON> said. 

   As previously reported, the <ORGANIZATION>Bank of England</ORGANIZATION> is believed to have sold sterling on <DATE>Wednesday</DATE> to slow the pound's recent surge. 
The <ORGANIZATION>U.S. Federal Reserve Board</ORGANIZATION> was also rumored to have sold dollars <DATE>Wednesday</DATE> in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> and yesterday in <LOCATION>Asia</LOCATION> to damp the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> currency's rise. 

   The rumors, though unsubstantiated, prevented many market participants from acting on their generally bullish near-term view of both currencies. 

   Traders have been cautious about opening or maintaining large currency positions in the wake of a <DATE>Feb. 22</DATE> agreement meant to stabilize exchange rates between the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> and five top economic allies. 

   "They really don't want the market to run away with the currency," said <PERSON>J. Steven Stekly</PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION>Bank of Boston</ORGANIZATION> trader, referring to the <ORGANIZATION>Bank of England</ORGANIZATION>'s rumored sterling intervention. 

   In late <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> trading, the dollar stood at <MONEY>1.8590 West German marks</MONEY>, off from 1.8600 the day before. 
The dollar slipped to 153.38 Japanese yen from 153.69. 
The British pound eased to <MONEY>$1.5875</MONEY> from <MONEY>$1.5933</MONEY>, and dipped to <MONEY>2.9512 marks</MONEY> from 2.9635. 

   In early trading in <LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION> <DATE>Friday</DATE> the dollar rose against the Japanese currency to <MONEY>153.45 yen</MONEY> from 153.38 in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> <TIME>yesterday afternoon</TIME>. 

   Despite the downward revision of <DATE>January</DATE> retail sales, traders said the <DATE>February</DATE> figure supports the market's more positive attitude toward the dollar that has stemmed from earlier economic reports. 
And so-called technical analysis of charts illustrating the dollar's recent trading pattern -- which many dealers study -- indicates continued gains by the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> currency. 

   "Technically and fundamentally, the dollar is in a bullish trend for the near term," said <PERSON>John W. Baker</PERSON>, chief foreign-exchange trader at <ORGANIZATION>Bank Julius Baer &amp; Co.</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>. 
"We've been having higher highs and high lows each day. 
The dollar is trading beautifully in an up channel." 

   "Sterling is also following a perfectly bullish trend line" on charts, <PERSON>Mr. Baker</PERSON> said. 

   On the <ORGANIZATION>Commodity Exchange</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>, gold for <DATE>March</DATE> delivery rose <MONEY>$1.80</MONEY> an ounce, to <MONEY>$408.70</MONEY>, in moderate trading. 
The estimated volume was 3.1 million ounces. 

   Gold was quoted at <MONEY>$409.20</MONEY> an ounce in early trading <DATE>Friday</DATE> in <LOCATION>Hong Kong</LOCATION>. 

