<HL> Currency Markets: Dollar Drops a Bit; U.K. Isn't Boosting Rates, Official Says </HL>
<AUTHOR> Charles W. Stevens (WSJ Staff) </AUTHOR>
<SO> </SO>
<CO> EUROP JAPAN FREST CANDA </CO>
<IN> MON FRX PCS CMD </IN>
<TEXT>
   The dollar eased in quiet foreign-exchange dealings yesterday as market participants awaited <DATE>Friday</DATE>'s report on <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> merchandise trade. 

   Traders' expectations that the report covering <DATE>December</DATE> will show a continued shrinkage of the trade deficit supported the dollar in a stable but narrow trading range. 
Despite such optimism, uncertainty about the <ORGANIZATION>Commerce Department</ORGANIZATION>'s trade data discouraged many dealers from taking large positions. 

   "People are perfectly content to stay inactive until the trade number," <PERSON>Robert Hatcher</PERSON>, vice president and corporate foreign-exchange dealer at <ORGANIZATION>Barclays Bank PLC</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>, said. 

   With activity in the dollar stymied by anticipation of the trade data, "cross-trading" increased among the British pound, West German mark and Japanese yen. 
"That's typical of a market that isn't confident on where the dollar's heading," <PERSON>Mr. Hatcher</PERSON> said. 

   In cross-trading, the pound eased against the mark yesterday after British Chancellor of the Exchequer <PERSON>Nigel Lawson</PERSON> said he doesn't see any "great pressure" for higher British interest rates. 
The comment, made in <LOCATION>Brussels</LOCATION> after a meeting of the finance ministers of the <ORGANIZATION>European Community</ORGANIZATION>, contradicted market speculation that an official rate increase is in the works. 

   Higher British interest rates would increase the appeal of sterling-denominated investments and, in turn, demand for sterling. 
In late <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> trading yesterday, the pound stood at <MONEY>2.9679 marks</MONEY>, off from 2.9738 <DATE>Monday</DATE>. 

   When asked by reporters whether he saw a need to increase interest rates in the near term, <PERSON>Mr. Lawson</PERSON> said he would act "when necessary." 

   <PERSON>Mr. Lawson</PERSON> also told reporters that <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> has for the past year pegged the pound in line with the eight currencies in the exchange-rate mechanism of the <ORGANIZATION>European Monetary System</ORGANIZATION>. 
Asked whether <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> would join the <ORGANIZATION>EMS</ORGANIZATION> mechanism, <PERSON>Mr. Lawson</PERSON> said, "We hope to continue with a policy that encourages exchange-rate stability." 
He declined to be more specific. 

   His comment concerning sterling's relationship to the <ORGANIZATION>EMS</ORGANIZATION> didn't immediately affect the market, but it confirmed speculation. 
From watching the <ORGANIZATION>Bank of England</ORGANIZATION>'s pattern of foreign-exchange-market intervention over most of last year, dealers have assumed that <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> is enforcing a trading range for sterling between 2.95 and <MONEY>3.00 marks</MONEY>. 
The <ORGANIZATION>EMS</ORGANIZATION> is centered around the West German currency. 
"Sterling has been a shadow member of the <ORGANIZATION>EMS</ORGANIZATION> for several months," said <ORGANIZATION>Barclays</ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON>Mr. Hatcher</PERSON>. 

   The pound inched higher against the dollar, as did most other major currencies yesterday. 
The pound firmed to <MONEY>$1.7510</MONEY> from <MONEY>$1.7495</MONEY>, while the dollar eased to <MONEY>1.6950 marks</MONEY>, from 1.6998. 
The dollar was unchanged at <MONEY>128.83 yen</MONEY>. 

   In midmorning <LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION> trading <DATE>Wednesday</DATE>, the dollar was quoted at <MONEY>129.05 yen</MONEY>. 

