<HL> Currency Markets: Baker Remarks Help Sterling Continue Rally --- U.S. Treasury Chief Seeks To Allay Fears of Shift In U.K. Monetary Policy </HL>
<AUTHOR> Charles W. Stevens (WSJ Staff) </AUTHOR>
<SO> </SO>
<CO> FREST JAPAN EUROP CANDA </CO>
<IN> MON FRX PCS CMD </IN>
<TEXT>
   Sterling's rally stretched into its fifth day yesterday, encouraged by remarks of <ORGANIZATION>U.S. Treasury</ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON>James Baker</PERSON> endorsing the recent shift in British monetary policy. 

   Trading again focused on the pound's exchange rate with the West German currency, which rose <PERCENT>0.3%</PERCENT> to <MONEY>3.0822 marks</MONEY> in late <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> trading yesterday, from 3.0720 <DATE>Tuesday</DATE>. 
Meanwhile, the dollar firmed against most major currencies. 

   Sterling gave up some of its gains from earlier in the day, following selling to take profits on its rise over the past week. 
The pound finished the <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> trading day at <MONEY>$1.8445</MONEY>, up slightly from <MONEY>$1.8424</MONEY> the day before. 

   Sterling's so-called "cross rate" with the West German currency has been playing center stage in the foreign exchange market since the <ORGANIZATION>Bank of England</ORGANIZATION>, for the first time in more than a year, let the pound rise above <MONEY>3.00 marks</MONEY> <DATE>Monday</DATE>. 

   Previously, the British central bank maintained a tight cap on the pound's value by intervening in currency markets to sell sterling, thus reducing its exchange rate and thereby helping British exporters. 
But British Prime Minister <PERSON>Margaret Thatcher</PERSON> said <DATE>Tuesday</DATE> that the <ORGANIZATION>Bank of England</ORGANIZATION> wouldn't intervene or cut interest rates to weaken sterling because of concerns about inflation heating up in <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION>'s buoyant economy. 

   In <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION>Treasury</ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON>Baker</PERSON> voiced support for the shift in British monetary policy, saying that the change reflected monetary policy considerations within <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> and in relation to other currencies in the <ORGANIZATION>European Monetary System</ORGANIZATION>, an eight-currency exchange rate mechanism centered on the mark. 

   <PERSON>Mr. Baker</PERSON>'s remarks to the congressional <ORGANIZATION>Joint Economic Committee</ORGANIZATION> removed some speculation about British monetary policy. 
<PERSON>Mrs. Thatcher</PERSON>'s statement <DATE>Tuesday</DATE> had prompted speculation that the monetary policy was shifting from the <ORGANIZATION>Group of Seven</ORGANIZATION>'s agreement on exchange-rate stability. 
The <ORGANIZATION>Group of Seven</ORGANIZATION> nations -- <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION>, the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>West Germany</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>France</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Canada</LOCATION>, and <LOCATION>Italy</LOCATION> -- reaffirmed the agreement last <DATE>December</DATE>. 

   <PERSON>Mr. Baker</PERSON> said the <PERSON>Thatcher</PERSON> statement isn't "in any way" contrary to the <ORGANIZATION>Group of Seven</ORGANIZATION> agreement and that <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> remains "fully committed" to the accord. 

   With relatively high interest rates and a booming economy in <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION>, traders predicted the pound's rally will carry sterling still higher against the West German currency, to <MONEY>3.10 marks</MONEY>. 
"This is not over. 
We have to try 3.10 (marks) to see if the <ORGANIZATION>Bank of England</ORGANIZATION> is there" to stem sterling's rise, said <PERSON>Francoise Soares-Kemp</PERSON>, treasury vice president at <ORGANIZATION>Credit Suisse</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>. 

   But some market participants began expressing wariness about sterling's outlook. 
"It has the potential to disappoint people very quickly. 
There's a lot of speculative buying," said <PERSON>Jeff Mondschein</PERSON>, vice president and foreign exchange manager at <ORGANIZATION>Merrill Lynch Capital Markets</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>. 
Speculators could rush out of the currency just as quickly as they came in it, he said. 
"There are also a lot of positions looking to take profits. 
Some people have been playing it since (sterling was) 2.96" marks, <PERSON>Mr. Mondschein</PERSON> added. 

   In other dealings, the dollar firmed to <MONEY>1.6710 marks</MONEY>, from 1.6674, and to <MONEY>128.15 yen</MONEY>, from 127.85. 
In early <LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION> trading <DATE>Thursday</DATE>, it opened at <MONEY>128.25 yen</MONEY>. 

   Traders said the dollar avoided a possible pitfall from the Super <DATE>Tuesday</DATE> voting results. 
A strong showing by Rep. <PERSON>Richard Gephardt</PERSON>, which didn't occur, could have put the dollar under heavy pressure because his views were considered protectionist and harmful to the economy. 

   On the <ORGANIZATION>Commodity Exchange</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>, gold for current delivery rose <MONEY>90 cents</MONEY> an ounce to <MONEY>$436.20</MONEY> in moderate trading. 
The estimated volume was 2.8 million ounces. 

