<HL> Currency Markets: Sterling Surges, Causing Action By Central Bank --- Bullish Report in London Is Cited in Sharp Rally; Dollar Climbs Slightly </HL>
<AUTHOR> Charles W. Stevens (WSJ Staff) </AUTHOR>
<SO> </SO>
<CO> FREST JAPAN EUROP CANDA </CO>
<IN> PCS CMD MON FRX </IN>
<TEXT>
   A bullish article on sterling by a <ORGANIZATION>Goldman, Sachs &amp; Co.</ORGANIZATION> economist in <LOCATION>London</LOCATION> was cited in yesterday's sharp rally by the British currency. 

   The pound surged <PERCENT>1.1%</PERCENT> to stand at <MONEY>$1.8815</MONEY> in late <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> trading, from <MONEY>$1.8605</MONEY> <DATE>Friday</DATE>, and climbed <PERCENT>1.3%</PERCENT> to <MONEY>3.16 marks</MONEY>, from 3.12 in heavy trading. 

   The pound's sudden rally prompted the <ORGANIZATION>Bank of England</ORGANIZATION> to intervene in foreign exchange trading by selling sterling for dollars, and thus capping the British currency's rise for the time being. 
But traders and economists continued to voice optimism for the pound. 

   In other trading, the dollar firmed slightly. 

   The article cited by many traders for kicking off <DATE>Monday</DATE>'s rally appeared in the <DATE>Sunday</DATE> Times of <LOCATION>London</LOCATION> and was written by <ORGANIZATION>Goldman Sachs</ORGANIZATION>'s London-based chief international economist, <PERSON>David Morrison</PERSON>, an influential exchange-rate forecaster. 
In a recent report, <PERSON>Mr. Morrison</PERSON> said the pound could rise to <MONEY>$2</MONEY> within six months and reach the 3.2-mark level in the same period. 

   According to traders, the market reacted to a reassertion of that forecast in the <DATE>Sunday</DATE> article and a statement that British exporters could tolerate even higher sterling exchange rates. 
A stronger currency makes British exports more costly for foreign consumers. 

   The article reinforced strong bullish sentiment toward sterling already established in the market. 
Because of a strong economy and relatively high interest rates, the pound has been a darling among currency traders this year. 
"A lot of (economic) fundamentals are in favor of the <LOCATION>U.K.</LOCATION> 
This trend could possibly continue," <PERSON>Cynthia H. Johnson</PERSON>, vice president of foreign exchange at <ORGANIZATION>Lloyds Bank PLC</ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> unit. 

   <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION>'s high interest rates have become particularly attractive to traders recently because of the dollar's stability in the market. 
Unable to profit from the dollar's volatility, traders have bought sterling to earn its higher yields. 
Yesterday, three-month Eurosterling deposits yielded <PERCENT>8 5/16%</PERCENT>, in contrast to 7 3/8 for similar dollar investments, and <PERCENT>3 9/16%</PERCENT> for three-month Euromark deposits. 

   "Investors still like to buy sterling and hold it," said <PERSON>Antonio Bustamante</PERSON>, global foreign exchange manager at <ORGANIZATION>Marine Midland Bank</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>. 

   In <PERSON>Mr. Morrison</PERSON>'s most recent monthly economic report for <ORGANIZATION>Goldman Sachs</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>U.K.</LOCATION> economic growth for this year is estimated at <PERCENT>3.6%</PERCENT>, in contrast to a <PERCENT>1.8%</PERCENT> forecast for West German economic expansion, and <PERCENT>2.2%</PERCENT> for the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> 

   On the <ORGANIZATION>Commodity Exchange</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>, gold for current delivery rose <MONEY>$3.60</MONEY> an ounce to <MONEY>$447.30</MONEY> in light trading. 
The estimated volume was 1.2 million ounces. 

   Gold was quoted at <MONEY>$447.40</MONEY> an ounce in early trading <DATE>Tuesday</DATE> in <LOCATION>Hong Kong</LOCATION>. 

