<HL> Currency Markets: High-Yielding Currencies Rise As Dollar Drops --- Australia, Britain Intervene To Try to Stem Increases In Their Monetary Units </HL>
<AUTHOR> Charles W. Stevens (WSJ Staff) </AUTHOR>
<SO> </SO>
<CO> EUROP JAPAN FREST CANDA </CO>
<IN> MON FRX PCS CMD </IN>
<TEXT>
   High-yielding currencies continued surging yesterday, prompting the British and Australian central banks to intervene in foreign exchange markets to restrain the rise of their currencies, dealers said. 

   The dollar was slightly weaker against most other major currencies. 
However, according to some dealers, the dollar is benefiting indirectly from so-called cross-trading between non-dollar currencies. 
Cross-trading has increased recently as part of the general movement into such high-interest rate currencies as the British pound and the Australian dollar, from such relatively low-yielding currencies as the West German mark and yen. 

   The dollar lost the most ground to the pound, as the British currency climbed <PERCENT>0.3%</PERCENT> to stand at <MONEY>$1.8375</MONEY> in late <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> trading, from <MONEY>$1.8315</MONEY> <DATE>Tuesday</DATE>. 
Of more concern to British monetary authorities, however, was sterling's rise against the mark following sharp gains over the past two weeks. 
The stronger pound hurts British exporters by making <LOCATION>U.K.</LOCATION> goods more expensive abroad. 

   In early <LOCATION>London</LOCATION> trading the <ORGANIZATION>Bank of England</ORGANIZATION> sold sterling, according to traders, as the pound climbed to <MONEY>3.11 marks</MONEY>. 
By late <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> trading, sterling was quoted at <MONEY>3.1063 marks</MONEY>. 
That was still up <PERCENT>0.2%</PERCENT> from 3.0987 <DATE>Tuesday</DATE>. 

   In <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>, traders said the <ORGANIZATION>U.S. Federal Reserve</ORGANIZATION>, acting on behalf of the <ORGANIZATION>Reserve Bank of Australia</ORGANIZATION>, sold Australian dollars in the market to turn back the currency's advance. 
The Australian dollar stood at <MONEY>73.96 U.S. cents</MONEY> in late <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> trading yesterday, down from 74.18 <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> cents <DATE>Tuesday</DATE>. 

   The Canadian dollar, another currency offering high yields, continued to rally, climbing to <MONEY>80.43 U.S. cents</MONEY>, from <MONEY>80.25 U.S. cents</MONEY>. 

   Higher interest rates for deposits of these currencies make them more attractive to hold than other currencies, and increase the demand for them. 
The yields on three-month Eurocurrency deposits are <PERCENT>8.63%</PERCENT> for sterling, <PERCENT>10.31%</PERCENT> for Australian dollars, and <PERCENT>8.5%</PERCENT> for Canadian dollars. 
These rates stand in sharp contrast to yields for similar deposits of <PERCENT>6.84%</PERCENT> for dollars and <PERCENT>3.38%</PERCENT> for marks. 

   "There's a great deal of demand for these currencies and that (upward) pressure will probably continue," said <PERSON>Albert Soria</PERSON>, vice president and foreign exchange manager at <ORGANIZATION>Swiss Bank Corp.</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>. 

   In other trading, the dollar eased slightly to <MONEY>1.6905 marks</MONEY>, from 1.6919, and to <MONEY>126.75 yen</MONEY>, from 127.05. 

   In <LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION>, the dollar opened <DATE>Thursday</DATE> at 126.75, below its quote of <MONEY>127.15 yen</MONEY> at the end of <DATE>Wednesday</DATE>'s <LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION> session. 

   On the <ORGANIZATION>Commodity Exchange</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>, gold for current delivery rose <MONEY>$2.40</MONEY> an ounce to <MONEY>$451.10</MONEY> in heavy trading. 
The estimated volume was six million ounces. 

