<HL> Currency Markets: Sterling Gains Erased by Talk Of Intervention --- Profit-Taking Also Stalls Rally Linked to Budget; Dollar Posts Increases </HL>
<AUTHOR> Charles W. Stevens (WSJ Staff) </AUTHOR>
<SO> </SO>
<CO> EUROP CANDA FREST JAPAN </CO>
<IN> MON PCS CMD FRX </IN>
<TEXT>
   Profit-taking and rumored central bank intervention reversed a brief but sharp rally in sterling yesterday immediately after the British government released its budget proposal. 

   The pound began soaring around midday <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> time as British Chancellor of the Exchequer <PERSON>Nigel Lawson</PERSON> presented the <LOCATION>U.K.</LOCATION> government's proposed budget for the fiscal year beginning in <DATE>April</DATE>. 
As <PERSON>Mr. Lawson</PERSON> concluded his remarks, the pound was already under selling pressure from traders taking profits on the currency's quick runup. 

   "It wasn't exactly a quiet day," said <PERSON>John I. Shupe</PERSON>, the sterling trader at <ORGANIZATION>Royal Bank of Canada</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>. 

   In late <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> trading the pound stood at <MONEY>$1.8455</MONEY>, off <PERCENT>0.3%</PERCENT> from <MONEY>$1.8515</MONEY> <DATE>Monday</DATE>. 
But the day's overall movement in exchange rates masked a hectic trading period during <PERSON>Mr. Lawson</PERSON>'s budget speech in which the pound soared <PERCENT>0.5%</PERCENT> to <MONEY>$1.86</MONEY>, from <MONEY>$1.8505</MONEY> during the first 30 minutes of the chancellor's remarks. 

   Many <LOCATION>London</LOCATION> banks stopped quoting prices for sterling while they watched the speech on television, and many other <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> banks withdrew from the market to await news service stories on the budget plan, which channeled most trading through the broker market. 

   Against the mark, the pound climbed to an intraday high of <MONEY>3.0930 marks</MONEY>, from 3.0827 <DATE>Monday</DATE>, before falling back to 3.0838 late in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>. 

   A bullish British budget for fiscal <DATE>1989</DATE> was generally expected by market participants, who had been bidding sterling higher over most of the past two weeks partly in anticipation of the news. 
The actual budget proposal, however, was interpreted by many traders as being more positive for sterling than earlier speculation. 

   <PERSON>Michael D. Andrews</PERSON>, vice president and foreign exchange economist at <ORGANIZATION>Irving Trust Co.</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>, said the projection of a larger-than-expected budget surplus "is an indication of the economy's overall health." 
He added that the absence of government borrowings will increase the demand and prices for existing British government bonds, or gilts, attracting foreigners seeking capital gains potential. 
"Foreigners will have to buy sterling to buy gilts," <PERSON>Mr. Andrews</PERSON> said, explaining the bullish impact on the pound. 

   <PERSON>Mr. Lawson</PERSON>'s forecast of a government surplus of <MONEY>#3 billion</MONEY> (<MONEY>$5.54 billion</MONEY>) for fiscal <DATE>1989</DATE> exceeded market expectations of a <MONEY>#2 billion</MONEY> surplus. 

   Sterling's slide yesterday came almost as quickly as its rise. 
"What we saw was profit-taking. 
People had some very nice profits in the cross positions," said <PERSON>Cynthia H. Johnson</PERSON>, vice president and corporate foreign exchange manager at <ORGANIZATION>Lloyds Bank PLC</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>, referring to trades between sterling and marks. 

   The wave of selling also prompted rumors that the <ORGANIZATION>Bank of England</ORGANIZATION> intervened in the market to stem sterling's rise. 
A spokesman at the British central bank declined to comment on the rumors. 
The lack of confirmation of intervention did little to discourage selling on the fear that the <ORGANIZATION>Bank of England</ORGANIZATION> was blocking further appreciation of sterling. 
"I'd rather trade off of rumors than facts. 
By the time it's confirmed it doesn't matter anymore," said <ORGANIZATION>Royal Bank</ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON>Mr. Shupe</PERSON>. 

   Last week British Prime Minister <PERSON>Margaret Thatcher</PERSON> said <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> wouldn't any longer intervene in foreign exchange markets to contain the pound's appreciation because of concerns about inflation. 
The <ORGANIZATION>Bank of England</ORGANIZATION>'s intervention against the pound tends to be inflationary because by selling sterling in the foreign exchange market, it increases the money supply. 
Despite the policy announcement, many traders are wary of the <ORGANIZATION>Bank of England</ORGANIZATION> attempting to thwart the pound's rise if the currency nears <MONEY>3.10 marks</MONEY>. 

   In other dealings, the dollar firmed against the major currencies. 
Traders attributed the rise to position-squaring ahead of tomorrow's report on <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> merchandise trade. 
The dollar climbed yesterday to <MONEY>1.6710 marks</MONEY>, from 1.6650, and to <MONEY>127.45 yen</MONEY>, from 126.90. 

   The dollar opened <DATE>Wednesday</DATE> in <LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION> at <MONEY>127.38 yen</MONEY>, up from <MONEY>127.25 yen</MONEY> in closing trading <DATE>Tuesday</DATE>. 

   On the <ORGANIZATION>Commodity Exchange</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>, gold for current delivery rose <MONEY>$4.40</MONEY> an ounce to <MONEY>$446.30</MONEY> in moderate trading. 
The estimated volume was 3.2 million ounces. 

