By Charles W.                                                 
Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal</HL>
<DD> 02/18/87</DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO>
<IN> EUROP JAPAN CANDA FREST
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
FOREIGN-EXCHANGE MARKETS (FRX)
PRECIOUS METALS, STONES, GOLD, SILVER (PCS)
COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD) </IN>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was mixed against most major currencies in light trading yesterday as dealers awaited the latest word on the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> economy and monetary policy, scheduled for tomorrow. 

   Treasury Secretary <PERSON>James Baker</PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION>Federal Reserve Board</ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON>Paul Volcker</PERSON> are scheduled to testify before separate <ORGANIZATION>Senate</ORGANIZATION> panels tomorrow, and comments by either official could move currency rates, traders said. 
"People want to see whether <PERSON>Volcker</PERSON> and <PERSON>Baker</PERSON> are dancing to the same tune," said <PERSON>Peter Rogers</PERSON>, vice president and chief foreign-exchange dealer at <ORGANIZATION>Banca Nazionale Dell</ORGANIZATION>'Agricoltura, <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>. 

   <PERSON>Mr. Baker</PERSON> recently has maintained that "the market" should determine proper exchange rates between major world currencies. 
Previously, <PERSON>Mr. Baker</PERSON> led the effort to weaken the dollar to increase the competitiveness of <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> goods in international markets, and many speculators believe he still seeks a lower dollar. 
<PERSON>Mr. Volcker</PERSON>, meanwhile, frequently has voiced concern about a sharp decline in the dollar and its potential inflationary impact as imports become more expensive for Americans to buy. 

   The <ORGANIZATION>Commerce Department</ORGANIZATION> is scheduled to release tomorrow revised gross national product figures for the <DATE>final quarter of 1986</DATE>. 
Traders and analysts generally are looking for a modest upward revision of the <PERCENT>1.7%</PERCENT> growth rate originally reported. 
"A slight upward revision will have no effect, but a large downward revision would be detrimental for the dollar," <PERSON>Mr. Rogers</PERSON> said. 

   In late <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> trading yesterday, the dollar stood at <MONEY>1.8178 West German marks</MONEY>, down from 1.8210 in late <LOCATION>London</LOCATION> dealings <DATE>Monday</DATE>. 
<LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> trading was idle <DATE>Monday</DATE> for the <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION>'s birthday holiday. 
The dollar also eased yesterday to 153.40 Japanese yen, from 153.55, but firmed to 1.5368 Swiss francs, from 1.5355. 
The British pound climbed to <MONEY>$1.5290</MONEY>, from <MONEY>$1.5213</MONEY>. 

   In early trading in <LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION> <DATE>Wednesday</DATE>, the dollar rose against the Japanese currency to <MONEY>153.43 yen</MONEY> from 153.40 in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> <TIME>yesterday afternoon</TIME>. 

