<HL> Currency Markets: Pound Surges, Despite Fed's Move to Curb It --- Britain, Clarifying Policy, Says Rein on Currency Is Looser; Dollar Falls </HL>
<AUTHOR> Charles W. Stevens and Peter Torday (WSJ Staff) </AUTHOR>
<SO> </SO>
<CO> EUROP JAPAN FREST CANDA </CO>
<IN> MON FRX PCS CMD </IN>
<TEXT>
   The British pound continued its surge in foreign-exchange trading yesterday but ran into resistance from the <ORGANIZATION>U.S. Federal Reserve</ORGANIZATION>. 

   The dollar, meanwhile, fell in moderately active <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> trading despite the <ORGANIZATION>Fed</ORGANIZATION>'s attempts to prop it up and limit the pound's gains. 

   According to dealers at several <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> banks, the <ORGANIZATION>Fed</ORGANIZATION> sold <MONEY>#70 million</MONEY> (<MONEY>$131.8 million</MONEY>) of the British currency in afternoon trading after sterling climbed to its intraday highs of <MONEY>$1.8825</MONEY> and 3.1250 West German marks. 
The intervention against the pound was probably done on behalf of the <ORGANIZATION>Bank of England</ORGANIZATION>, which was concerned with the market's new rush to the British currency, traders said. 

   In late <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> trading, the pound stood at <MONEY>$1.8755</MONEY>, up <PERCENT>0.5%</PERCENT> from <MONEY>$1.8660</MONEY> late <DATE>Tuesday</DATE>. 
Over the past two weeks, the pound has gained <PERCENT>2.8%</PERCENT> against the dollar after an announced shift in British monetary policy made the fight against inflation the top priority. 

   The pound's latest gains followed remarks made in <LOCATION>London</LOCATION> by <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION>'s top financial official. 

   Speaking to a parliamentary panel, Chancellor of the Exchequer <PERSON>Nigel Lawson</PERSON> confirmed that <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> had abandoned tight management of the pound's value and indicated that the currency might be allowed to rise further. 
His comments appeared to end a period of confusion over British exchange-rate policy that had disturbed the currency markets. 

   The pound soared after <PERSON>Mr. Lawson</PERSON>'s remarks. 
<LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> had been striving for about a year to keep the currency below 3.00 West German marks to try to keep British exports competitive in European markets. 
It stopped defending that level early this month, but <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION>'s new stance hadn't been clear to foreign-exchange traders before yesterday. 

   The pound closed yesterday in <LOCATION>London</LOCATION> at <MONEY>3.1227 marks</MONEY>, compared with <MONEY>3.1077 marks</MONEY> a day earlier. 

   The new British strategy apparently means British interest rates will remain relatively high. 
That is attracting a huge flow of capital into sterling as investors seek higher yields than are available in the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>West Germany</LOCATION> or <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>. 

   <PERSON>Mr. Lawson</PERSON>, whose job is analogous to that of <ORGANIZATION>Treasury</ORGANIZATION> secretary in the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION>, said sterling's stabilization over the past year ended a six-year decline in the currency that had threatened to undermine <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION>'s fight against inflation. 
The pound's value averaged <MONEY>2.94 marks</MONEY> last year, compared with <MONEY>4.56 marks</MONEY> in <DATE>1981</DATE>. 

   Today's stable to slightly firmer pound helps British exporters keep their prices steady and indirectly holds down costs throughout the entire domestic economy, <PERSON>Mr. Lawson</PERSON> said. 

   He suggested that sterling might be allowed to rise still further, saying, "It may be that we become so successful that we can have a gradually appreciating exchange rate." 

   Traders in the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> said yesterday's <ORGANIZATION>Fed</ORGANIZATION> intervention didn't seem aimed at stopping the pound's rise completely. 

   "It's just slowing down any movements, keeping the rise in an orderly fashion and from getting out of hand," <PERSON>John I. Shupe</PERSON>, the sterling dealer at <ORGANIZATION>Royal Bank of Canada</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>, said. 

   Meanwhile, despite the reported <ORGANIZATION>Fed</ORGANIZATION> activity, the dollar stood in late <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> trading yesterday at <MONEY>1.6635 marks</MONEY>, down from <MONEY>1.6690 marks</MONEY> late <DATE>Tuesday</DATE>, and at 125.10 Japanese yen, off from 125.25 late <DATE>Tuesday</DATE>. 

   In midmorning <LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION> trading <DATE>Thursday</DATE>, the dollar was quoted at <MONEY>125.25 yen</MONEY>. 

   One dealer at a major bank said the dollar eased in part because of a large order to buy currency futures placed on <LOCATION>Chicago</LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION>International Monetary Market</ORGANIZATION> by a major Chicago-based commodities house. 

   On the <ORGANIZATION>Commodity Exchange</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>, gold for current delivery rose <MONEY>$2.40</MONEY> an ounce to <MONEY>$457.80</MONEY> in heavy trading. 
Estimated volume was 7.5 million ounces. 

