<HL> Currency Markets:
British Debate
Is Seen on Role
In Rate System
---
Some Analysts Say Thatcher
Ready to Weigh Joining
8-Nation European Unit
---
By Charles W. Stevens
Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal</HL>
<DD> 06/15/87</DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO>
<IN> CANDA FREST JAPAN EUROP
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD)
FOREIGN-EXCHANGE MARKETS (FRX)
PRECIOUS METALS, STONES, GOLD, SILVER (PCS) </IN>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister <PERSON>Margaret Thatcher</PERSON>'s reelection revives speculation over whether <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> will join the European Monetary System. 

   But a decision is probably months away, currency traders and economists say. 

   Some leading cabinet members in the Conservative Party government favor British membership in the eight-currency system of managed exchange rates. 
But <PERSON>Mrs. Thatcher</PERSON> has blocked <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION>'s entry ever since the system was established in <DATE>1979</DATE>. 
In the wake of her third consecutive election victory last week, <PERSON>Mrs. Thatcher</PERSON> may be more amenable to changing her mind, some analysts say. 

   "It's been on hold from a political standpoint and now will come up for consideration," <PERSON>Trevor W. Woodland</PERSON>, vice president, foreign exchange, at <ORGANIZATION>Harris Trust &amp; Savings Bank</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>Chicago</LOCATION>, says. 

   <PERSON>David Morrison</PERSON>, vice president and chief international economist at <ORGANIZATION>Goldman Sachs International Corp.</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>London</LOCATION>, says membership will be "the major policy issue being discussed over the next few months in <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION>." 
He sees a <PERCENT>60%</PERCENT> chance that <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> will join. 

   "I'm penciling it in for <DATE>September</DATE> or <DATE>October</DATE>," he says. 

   The main reason for joining would be to bring exchange-rate stability between <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> and its main trading partners in <LOCATION>Europe</LOCATION>. 
With <LOCATION>Europe</LOCATION> receiving about <PERCENT>60%</PERCENT> of British exports compared with the <PERCENT>10%</PERCENT> bound for the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION>, sterling's relation to European currencies such as the West German mark is vital. 

   The mark is the financial anchor in the <ORGANIZATION>EMS</ORGANIZATION>, which also includes the currencies of <LOCATION>France</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Italy</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Belgium</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Luxembourg</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Denmark</LOCATION>, the <LOCATION>Netherlands</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Ireland</LOCATION>. 

   "The competitiveness of British exporters is a key issue," <PERSON>Geoffrey Dennis</PERSON>, international economist at <ORGANIZATION>James Capel &amp; Co.</ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION>London</LOCATION> brokerage firm, says. 

   For that reason, <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> might want to join when the pound's value against those European currencies is below current levels. 
A weaker pound would make British goods less expensive for other Europeans. 

   <PERSON>Mr. Dennis</PERSON> and others predict that after a post-election rally takes the pound somewhere above three West German marks, the currency will weaken to <MONEY>2.85 marks</MONEY> by year's end. 
At that point, "we could just slide into the <ORGANIZATION>EMS</ORGANIZATION>," <PERSON>Mr. Dennis</PERSON> says. 

   Membership also might reduce the exchange-rate risk associated with sterling and thus help attract more foreign investment to <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION>, analysts say. 
That in turn could lead to higher prices for British government securities, or gilts, and lower British interest rates, providing another boost to the economy. 

   By eliminating sterling's downward spikes, which make imports more expensive, managed exchange rates also could help control inflation, <ORGANIZATION>EMS</ORGANIZATION> advocates say. 

   "It's a legitimate case (for joining), but that doesn't mean <PERSON>Mrs. Thatcher</PERSON> will go for it," <ORGANIZATION>Goldman</ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON>Mr. Morrison</PERSON> says. 

   There are a number of reasons. 

   Joining would mean ceding some control over monetary policy to outsiders, chiefly <LOCATION>West Germany</LOCATION>, around which the current system revolves. 
"In effect, it passes some independence over to the <ORGANIZATION>Bundesbank</ORGANIZATION>," the West German central bank, <PERSON>Mr. Dennis</PERSON> says. 

   And membership can get expensive. 
In a currency crisis, the <ORGANIZATION>Bank of England</ORGANIZATION> might have to spend heavily through currency market intervention to keep the pound's value within the limits that the <ORGANIZATION>EMS</ORGANIZATION> sets. 
Another collapse of oil prices, for instance, could easily trigger such a scenario for <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION>, a major exporter of <LOCATION>North Sea</LOCATION> crude. 

   Moreover, if <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> faced a prolonged problem with the pound while it was close to or in a recession, the <ORGANIZATION>Bank of England</ORGANIZATION> might have to boost interest rates to stabilize the currency -- and that probably would kill off any economic growth. 

   "You may have to make unpalatable decisions to raise interest rates at just the wrong time," <PERSON>Mr. Dennis</PERSON> says. 

   The first clue to <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION>'s intentions could come this month, when <PERSON>Mrs. Thatcher</PERSON> spells out her objectives for her third term in a ritual known as the queen's speech. 
The speech is prepared by the prime minister but read by the queen. 

   Because <PERSON>Mrs. Thatcher</PERSON> "has had such a major win in the election, she's going to have to be convinced" of the <ORGANIZATION>EMS</ORGANIZATION>'s merits, <PERSON>Mr. Morrison</PERSON> says. 

