   <DATE>Friday</DATE>'s Currency Activity
   A slight improvement in <DATE>April</DATE>'s <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> trade deficit and a smaller-than-expected rise in the producer price index for <DATE>May</DATE> helped the dollar strengthen against most major currencies. 

   Although the stronger dollar pressured sterling, the British pound rose against most other currencies after the ruling Conservative Party won a strong new parliamentary majority in <DATE>Thursday</DATE>'s general election. 

   In late <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> trading, the dollar stood at <MONEY>1.8105 West German marks</MONEY>, compared with 1.7920 late <DATE>Thursday</DATE>. 
The <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> currency also climbed to 143.98 Japanese yen from 142.33. 
The pound eased to <MONEY>$1.6566</MONEY> from <MONEY>$1.6630</MONEY>, but it rose to <MONEY>3.00 marks</MONEY> from 2.98. 

   Dealers said news that the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> merchandise trade deficit narrowed to <MONEY>$13.32 billion</MONEY> in <DATE>April</DATE> from <MONEY>$13.63 billion</MONEY> in <DATE>March</DATE> prompted short-covering by players expecting a more bearish figure. 

   More heartening, dealers said, was a <PERCENT>0.3%</PERCENT> increase in <DATE>May</DATE>'s producer price index after a <PERCENT>0.7%</PERCENT> rise for <DATE>April</DATE>. 
The market had been expecting about a <PERCENT>0.5%</PERCENT> increase for <DATE>May</DATE>. 
Dealers said the smaller rise eased inflation fears, which helped the dollar and the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> bond market. 

