<HL> Currency Markets: British Banks Raise Base Rate To Help Pound --- Increase Is Second in 4 Days; West German Bank Sold Huge Amount of Dollars </HL>
<AUTHOR> Stephen D. Moore (WSJ Staff) </AUTHOR>
<SO> </SO>
<CO> JAPAN CANDA FREST EUROP </CO>
<IN> MON PCS CMD FRX </IN>
<DATELINE> LONDON  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Major British banks raised their base rates one-half percentage point to <PERCENT>8.5%</PERCENT>, the second boost in four days, as <LOCATION>U.K.</LOCATION> authorities scrambled to stanch the pound's recent decline. 

   Separately, <LOCATION>West Germany</LOCATION>'s central bank reportedly exchanged at least <MONEY>$2 billion for marks</MONEY> through covert channels in the foreign-exchange market in the <DATE>last week of May</DATE>. 

   A further increase in <LOCATION>U.K.</LOCATION> base rates had been expected since <DATE>Friday</DATE>'s boost to <PERCENT>8%</PERCENT> from <PERCENT>7.5%</PERCENT>, their lowest level in a decade. 
Interbank credit markets had already discounted an additional one-half percentage point jump by <TIME>midday</TIME>, when the <ORGANIZATION>Bank of England</ORGANIZATION> signaled the latest rise by again lifting one of its main money-market intervention rates. 

   Within an hour, <ORGANIZATION>Barclays PLC</ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION>Lloyds Bank PLC</ORGANIZATION> and the <LOCATION>London</LOCATION> unit of <ORGANIZATION>Citicorp</ORGANIZATION> increased their base rates. 
The Barclays boost took effect immediately, while the other two banks' moves were effective at the close of business. 
Similar increases by <ORGANIZATION>National Westminster Bank PLC</ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Midland Bank PLC</ORGANIZATION> go into effect today. 
Base rates are the benchmark for commercial lending in <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION>. 

   The pound was relatively stable before and after the adjustment -- a marked contrast with last week's rate boost that came amid tumult in foreign-exchange markets. 
After opening weaker at about <MONEY>3.0875 marks</MONEY> from <DATE>Friday</DATE>'s close of <MONEY>3.0991 marks</MONEY>, the pound edged slightly above <MONEY>3.10 marks</MONEY> in listless morning dealing. 
The base-rate increase lifted the British currency to <MONEY>3.105 marks</MONEY> but it skidded to <MONEY>3.0933 marks</MONEY> in late trading. 

   A <ORGANIZATION>Bank of England</ORGANIZATION> spokesman said <DATE>Monday</DATE>'s action followed "an overall assessment" based on a range of economic factors that "pointed to the need for a further rise in interest rate." 

   He declined to elaborate. 

   Traders and economists fretted that the pound's lingering weakness could drive <LOCATION>U.K.</LOCATION> base rates up again soon. 
"It's still too early to put a floor on the downside for sterling," said <PERSON>Derek Walker</PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION>Midland Bank</ORGANIZATION> economist. 
"If sterling remains soft -- consistently below <MONEY>3.10 marks</MONEY> -- there is a chance of another rate rise." 

   <PERSON>Gavyn Davies</PERSON>, chief <LOCATION>U.K.</LOCATION> economist for <ORGANIZATION>Goldman, Sachs &amp; Co.</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>London</LOCATION>, was more confident that the present level of exchange rates and interest rates could stand in the continuing "cat-and-mouse game between the authorities and the (foreign-exchange) markets." 
The rate increases restore earlier differentials between British rates and lower rates prevailing in the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>West Germany</LOCATION>, he said. 

   Other analysts said the gradual narrowing of the rate gap was one reason for the pound's sudden fall last week. 
With the gap closing, sterling-denominated investments appeal less to investors. 

   Exchange rates stand at the same level as last <DATE>March</DATE>, when banks cut their base rates to <PERCENT>8.5%</PERCENT>, <PERSON>Mr. Davies</PERSON> said. 
That combination was acceptable enough to provide extended exchange-rate stability earlier this year, he added. 
The combination may work again. 

   In <LOCATION>West Germany</LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION>Bundesbank</ORGANIZATION> said its net monetary reserves fell to <MONEY>95.9 billion marks</MONEY> (<MONEY>$55.56 billion</MONEY>), down <MONEY>3.4 billion marks</MONEY>, in the week ended <DATE>May 31</DATE>, almost exclusively from foreign-currency sales. 
As most of the central bank's foreign reserves are in dollars, the drop reflected a massive unwinding of dollar positions it had built in support of the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> currency in the past two years. 
Because currency transactions are booked with a two-day delay, some of the dollar sales weren't included in its weekly statement, the <ORGANIZATION>Bundesbank</ORGANIZATION> said. 

   Dealers said they were stunned by the volume of the sales and the discretion with which the central bank managed to undertake the transaction. 
Observers were unable to confirm any of the interventions outside the fixing, as the central bank apparently used back channels and swore its partners to secrecy, they said. 

   Dealers said they were also surprised by the dollar's strength last week in light of the <ORGANIZATION>Bundesbank</ORGANIZATION>'s massive sales. 

   "It shows how bullish the market is on the dollar," said <PERSON>Michael Schnirel</PERSON>, a foreign-exchange dealer at <ORGANIZATION>Irving Trust Co.</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Frankfurt</LOCATION>. 

   Without the <ORGANIZATION>Bundesbank</ORGANIZATION>'s interventions, the dollar might have moved up even higher, other dealers added. 

   Analysts said the bank was taking advantage of the dollar's strength since midMay to reverse earlier currency interventions, which had bloated money supply. 

   By linking the small, but open dollar sales at the fixing with the massive covert transactions, the <ORGANIZATION>Bundesbank</ORGANIZATION> helped reinforce the myth of its own market power, said <PERSON>Giles Keating</PERSON>, economist at <ORGANIZATION>Credit Suisse First Boston</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>London</LOCATION>. 
"They wanted to create the impression that the limited interventions at the fixing had a strong impact on the market sentiment," he said. 
"With that, they were successful." 

   Foreign-exchange dealers and analysts said they expect the <ORGANIZATION>Bundesbank</ORGANIZATION> to continue its dollar sales in coming days. 
The central bank is believed to hold an estimated <MONEY>45 billion marks</MONEY> in dollar reserves in its accounts, far more than it would like to hold, dealers said. 

   In late afternoon <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> trading yesterday, the dollar fell to <MONEY>1.7136 marks</MONEY> from <MONEY>1.7278 marks</MONEY> <DATE>Friday</DATE>. 
It fell to <MONEY>125.78 yen</MONEY> from <MONEY>125.98 yen</MONEY>. 

   In midmorning trading in <LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION> <DATE>Tuesday</DATE>, the dollar was quoted at <MONEY>125.62 yen</MONEY>. 

   On <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>'s Commodity Exchange <DATE>Monday</DATE>, current-delivery gold settled at <MONEY>$462.90</MONEY> an ounce, down <MONEY>$1.90</MONEY>. 
Estimated volume was a moderate 3.2 million ounces. 

