<DATELINE> The U.S. dollar rose against most currencies yesterday  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   breaking out of its recent narrow trading range -- aided by the surging British pound. 

   Sterling continued to gain even though British commercial banks announced a cut in their base lending rate. 

   For the near term, many traders said they are bullish on the pound and cautiously optimistic about the dollar. 

   "The propensity is for the dollar to move up here," said <PERSON>Alan Rose</PERSON>, senior vice president and foreign-exchange manager at <ORGANIZATION>First Interstate Bank of California</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>Los Angeles</LOCATION>. 
"Sterling's strength and the (West German) mark's weakness are usually a bullish indicator for the dollar." 

   In discussing the dollar's recent rise, traders cited <DATE>Friday</DATE>'s better-than-expected February <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> employment data, which contrasted with the string of relatively weak reports about <LOCATION>West Germany</LOCATION>'s economy. 
"Right now, <LOCATION>Germany</LOCATION> doesn't look that great any more, and that's being reflected in the market," said <PERSON>Peter Wild</PERSON>, vice president of foreign exchange at <ORGANIZATION>Bank Julius Baer &amp; Co.</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>. 

   The dollar is also being carried along by the pound's rally, traders said. 
Some of sterling's biggest gains recently have come against the mark, and the flow of capital from marks into sterling is often accomplished through transactions involving the dollar. 
These transactions tend to strengthen the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> unit against the West German currency while weakening it against the pound, because in converting marks into sterling, traders often sell the mark to buy dollars and then use dollars to buy sterling. 

   The dollar climbed <PERCENT>0.8%</PERCENT> yesterday against the West German unit, to <MONEY>1.8595 marks</MONEY> from 1.8453, breaking out of its recent narrow trading range. 
The currency had traded narrowly because of market expectations of intervention, which stemmed from last month's agreement by the six largest industrialized nations to try to stabilize exchange rates. 

   Continuing last week's trend, sterling was strongest against its European counterparts as investors sought out <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION>'s relatively high interest rates and comparatively robust economy. 
In late <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> trading, the pound stood at <MONEY>2.9534 marks</MONEY>, up about <PERCENT>1%</PERCENT> from 2.9254 <DATE>Friday</DATE>. 
The pound firmed to <MONEY>$1.5883</MONEY> from <MONEY>$1.5853</MONEY> <DATE>Friday</DATE>. 

   Some currency traders were surprised by the timing of yesterday's announced reduction in the base rate. 
<LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION>'s major banks said they planned to cut the rate today, to <PERCENT>10.5%</PERCENT> from <PERCENT>11%</PERCENT>, after the <ORGANIZATION>Bank of England</ORGANIZATION> unexpectedly signaled yesterday that it favors such a cut. 

   The central bank lowered its key money-market intervention rates half a percentage point in late-morning trading. 
That prompted <ORGANIZATION>National Westminster Bank PLC</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION>'s biggest bank, to announce a half-point base rate cut. 
<LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION>'s three other major clearing banks -- <ORGANIZATION>Barclays Bank PLC</ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION>Midland Bank PLC</ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Lloyds Bank PLC</ORGANIZATION> -- quickly followed <ORGANIZATION>National Westminster</ORGANIZATION>'s lead. 

   A cut in the base rate theoretically makes sterling-denominated investments relatively less attractive, reducing demand for the currency. 

   Last week, the <ORGANIZATION>Bank of England</ORGANIZATION> tried to damp speculation about an imminent base-rate cut by lending funds to the money market at rates substantially above those set by the market. 
Yesterday, however, British authorities changed their minds about cutting interest rates after deciding that sterling's recent rise was firmly based "and more than a temporary blip," according to <ORGANIZATION>Treasury</ORGANIZATION> officials. 

   Soon after <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION>'s interest-rate announcement, the <ORGANIZATION>Bank of France</ORGANIZATION> reduced its seven-day repurchase rate to <PERCENT>8.5%</PERCENT> from <PERCENT>8.75%</PERCENT>. 
The repurchase rate generally sets the upper limit for <LOCATION>France</LOCATION>'s overnight-call money rate. 
Bank of <LOCATION>England</LOCATION> officials said the cuts weren't coordinated, although they conceded that the two central banks "might have been aware" of the other's move. 

   On the <ORGANIZATION>Commodity Exchange</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>, gold for <DATE>March</DATE> delivery fell <MONEY>$1.20</MONEY> an ounce to <MONEY>$405</MONEY> in light trading estimated at two million ounces. 

   Gold was quoted at <MONEY>$405</MONEY> an ounce in early trading <DATE>Tuesday</DATE> in <LOCATION>Hong Kong</LOCATION>. 

