<HL> Currency Markets: Dollar Posts a Gain Against the Pound; Other Trading Mixed </HL>
<AUTHOR> Peter R. Greiff (WSJ Special) </AUTHOR>
<SO> </SO>
<CO> EUROP CANDA FREST JAPAN </CO>
<IN> MON PCS CMD FRX </IN>
<DATELINE> NEW YORK  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was mixed, climbing to its highest level in three months against the pound, edging higher against the yen, and surrendering some of its recent gains against the mark. 

   Traders said the widespread unwinding of long-sterling/short-mark cross positions pushed the pound sharply lower. 
To unwind the sterling-mark positions, traders had to buy marks, which boosted that currency against the dollar. 
A broad direct move out of sterling and into dollars contributed to the pound's weakness. 

   Bearish statements by <ORGANIZATION>Bank of Japan</ORGANIZATION> Governor <PERSON>Satoshi Sumita</PERSON> about the dollar's long-term prospects and vague rumors of central-bank intervention in <LOCATION>Europe</LOCATION> also temporarily helped the mark. 

   In late afternoon <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> trading, the dollar was quoted at <MONEY>1.7310 marks</MONEY>, down from <MONEY>1.7328 marks</MONEY> late <DATE>Tuesday</DATE>, and at <MONEY>125.43 yen</MONEY>, up from <MONEY>125.23 yen</MONEY>. 

   In early trading in <LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION> <DATE>Thursday</DATE>, the dollar opened at <MONEY>125.50 yen</MONEY>. 

   The pound was quoted <DATE>Wednesday</DATE> at <MONEY>$1.8136</MONEY>, down from <MONEY>$1.8360</MONEY> late <DATE>Tuesday</DATE>, and at <MONEY>3.1384 marks</MONEY>, down from <MONEY>3.1800 marks</MONEY>. 
It was the lowest finish for the pound against the dollar since the close of <MONEY>$1.7745</MONEY> on <DATE>March 4</DATE>. 

   The unwinding of <ORGANIZATION>sterling/mark</ORGANIZATION> cross positions was triggered by the short-term interest-rate parity between the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> and British currencies achieved in the past week or so. 
As the <ORGANIZATION>U.S. Federal Reserve</ORGANIZATION> snugged short-term <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> rates, they caught up with and even surpassed rates that the <ORGANIZATION>Bank of England</ORGANIZATION> has been nudging lower to stem the pound's recent rise. 

   Many traders, however, said the pound's move lower was "overdone" and predicted a quick rebound. 

   The dollar inched higher against the yen as traders began to concentrate on a key currency which the dollar hasn't moved against since bullish <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> trade data for <DATE>March</DATE> were unveiled <DATE>May 17</DATE>. 

   Traders said movement by the dollar against the yen is difficult because of large orders to sell dollars for yen as the dollar moves higher. 

   On <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION>Commodity Exchange</ORGANIZATION>, June-delivery gold settled at <MONEY>$457.60</MONEY> an ounce, up <MONEY>$2.60</MONEY>. Estimated volume was a moderate 3.6 million ounces.  en
