<HL> Currency Markets:
Dollar Firms
Before Report
On U.S. Trade
---
Volume Is Light as Dealers
Say They Doubt Data
Will Boost the Currency
---
By Charles W. Stevens
Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal</HL>
<DD> 10/14/87</DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO>
<IN> EUROP JAPAN FREST CANDA
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
FOREIGN-EXCHANGE MARKETS (FRX)
PRECIOUS METALS, STONES, GOLD, SILVER (PCS)
COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD) </IN>
<TEXT>
   The dollar firmed in thin trading as dealers generally sat out the session or squared positions ahead of today's report on the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> merchandise trade balance for <DATE>August</DATE>. 

   The trade report, widely considered the most influential piece of economic data for exchange rates, isn't expected to contain good news for the dollar, many market participants say. 
Estimates of the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> deficit for the month range from about <MONEY>$13 billion</MONEY> to <MONEY>$15.5 billion</MONEY>. 

   Although forecasts generally call for a narrowing from the record <MONEY>$16.47 billion</MONEY> gap reported for <DATE>July</DATE>, many dealers say that even a deficit at the narrower end of the predicted range wouldn't be a sign of strength for the dollar. 

   "If the number is good, how good could it be?" 
<PERSON>Douglas Madison</PERSON>, a corporate trader at <ORGANIZATION>BankAmerica International</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>, asked. 
"Overall market sentiment is overwhelmingly bearish" for the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> currency, he said. 

   There was little trading in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> yesterday, with most activity coming earlier in Asian markets. 
The dollar's highs and lows for the day were reached in <LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION> trading. 

   The <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> currency first fell to an intraday low of 142.97 Japanese yen, triggering a burst of buying by investors who view <MONEY>143 yen</MONEY> as an important short-term support level. 
Then a <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> bank in <LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION>, believed to be operating on behalf of a <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> investment house, bought as much as <MONEY>$2 billion</MONEY> against the yen, traders said. 
That pushed the dollar to its intraday high of <MONEY>144.27 yen</MONEY>. 

   In late <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> trading, the dollar stood at <MONEY>143.89 yen</MONEY>, compared with 143.90 late <DATE>Monday</DATE>. 

   The dollar was quoted at <MONEY>144.15 yen</MONEY> in early <LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION> trading today. 

   Yesterday's trading in <LOCATION>Europe</LOCATION> continued to focus on the British pound's strength and the West German mark's relative weakness. 
The <ORGANIZATION>Bank of England</ORGANIZATION> intervened in the market for the second consecutive day to try to keep sterling below <MONEY>3.00 marks</MONEY>. 

   The pound "has the best economic house among the major traded currencies," <PERSON>John Lynam</PERSON>, vice president, foreign exchange, at <ORGANIZATION>Security Pacific National Bank</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>, said. 

   The pound is gathering support from recently stable oil prices and a relatively robust British economy, particularly compared with <LOCATION>West Germany</LOCATION>'s sluggish growth. 

   The mark has come under additional pressure since <DATE>Sunday</DATE>'s West German government announcement of a proposed <PERCENT>10%</PERCENT> withholding tax on interest income. 
In the longer term, "that has to cloud the investment environment in <LOCATION>West Germany</LOCATION>," <ORGANIZATION>BankAmerica</ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON>Mr. Madison</PERSON> said. 

   The dollar stood at <MONEY>1.8225 marks</MONEY> late yesterday in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>, compared with 1.8153 late <DATE>Monday</DATE>. 
The pound, meanwhile, continued to hover around <MONEY>3.00 marks</MONEY>. 

   On the <ORGANIZATION>Commodity Exchange</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>, gold for current delivery fell <MONEY>$2.60</MONEY> an ounce to <MONEY>$459.10</MONEY> in light trading. 
Estimated volume was 1.3 million ounces. 

   Gold was quoted at <MONEY>$458.95</MONEY> an ounce in early trading <DATE>today</DATE> in <LOCATION>Hong Kong</LOCATION>. 

