<HL> Currency Markets: Dollar Declines As Mark Moves Sharply Higher --- Sterling's Rally Continues Despite Some Confusion Over U.K. Statements </HL>
<AUTHOR> Michael R. Sesit (WSJ Staff) </AUTHOR>
<SO> </SO>
<CO> JAPAN FREST CANDA EUROP </CO>
<IN> MON FRX PCS CMD </IN>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell against most foreign currencies, and the West German mark moved sharply higher against its Continental European counterparts, in what dealers described as active but nervous trading. 

   Nearly all day, it looked as though the British pound's five trading-day gallop against the dollar had ended. 
But late in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> <DATE>Thursday</DATE>, sterling was bid up to <MONEY>$1.8460</MONEY>, slightly higher than the <MONEY>$1.8445</MONEY> quoted <DATE>late Wednesday</DATE>. 

   Also in late <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> trading, the dollar fell to <MONEY>1.6640 marks</MONEY> from <MONEY>1.6710 marks</MONEY> <DATE>Wednesday</DATE>, and to <MONEY>128.00 yen</MONEY> from 128.15. 

   The decline continued in early <LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION> trading, where the dollar opened at <MONEY>127.85 yen</MONEY>. 

   After hitting an intraday high of <MONEY>$1.8477</MONEY> in early Far Eastern trading, <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION>'s currency began falling on unfounded rumors that the <ORGANIZATION>Bank of England</ORGANIZATION> had placed orders to sell sterling. 
"It had the effect of inducing people to take profits or square positions," said <PERSON>Kenneth De La Salle</PERSON>, foreign exchange manager for <ORGANIZATION>National Westminster Bank</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>London</LOCATION>. 

   Currency dealers were whipsawed by contradictory statements to <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION>'s Parliament by Prime Minister <PERSON>Margaret Thatcher</PERSON> and Chancellor of the Exchequer <PERSON>Nigel Lawson</PERSON>. 
<PERSON>Mr. Lawson</PERSON> said sterling's recent rise against the mark was "unsustainable." 
Yet at the same time, the chancellor conceded that fighting inflation would remain at the "heart" of <LOCATION>London</LOCATION>'s economic policy and that interest rates would be used to damp inflationary expectations. 

   Minutes later, Prime Minister <PERSON>Thatcher</PERSON> also said that battling inflation was of "paramount importance" and that occasionally "adjustments are needed" in any exchange rate system. 
Yet, referring to the pound's recent strength, she added that "there is no way to buck the market." 

   For more than a year, <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> maintained a policy of holding the pound below <MONEY>3.00 marks</MONEY>, using aggressive intervention to do so when needed. 
The motive was to keep British exports competitive against the goods of its main European trading partners. 
But <DATE>Monday</DATE> the pound was allowed to rise above <MONEY>3.00 marks</MONEY>. 
And on <DATE>Tuesday</DATE>, <PERSON>Mrs. Thatcher</PERSON> said the central bank wouldn't intervene nor cut interest rates to weaken sterling. 

   Now, "People are confused about the signals coming from political leadership in the <LOCATION>U.K.</LOCATION>," said <PERSON>Charles Minnaar</PERSON>, a vice president at <ORGANIZATION>Chase Manhattan Bank</ORGANIZATION>. 

   Sterling's rise has been mostly attributed to <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION>'s relatively high interest rates. 
For example, the three-month <LOCATION>London</LOCATION> interbank offered rate, or Libor, for sterling is <PERCENT>8 15/16%</PERCENT>, compared with <PERCENT>6 7/8%</PERCENT> for <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> dollars and <PERCENT>3 7/16%</PERCENT> for marks. 
Libor is the rate at which major banks in <LOCATION>London</LOCATION> lend funds to each other. 

   At one point in yesterday's trading, the pound rose as high as <MONEY>3.0850 marks</MONEY> before falling back to <MONEY>3.0718 marks</MONEY> late in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>. 
Nevertheless, the British currency "is still well bid," said <PERSON>Robert Hatcher</PERSON>, a vice president at <ORGANIZATION>Barclays Bank PLC</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>. 

   Dealers attributed the pound's rebound in late <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> trading to the dollar's softness against other currencies, as well as thin late afternoon markets, where one dealer said a <MONEY>$10 million</MONEY> or <MONEY>$15 million</MONEY> order could easily move exchange rates. 
With "no clear direction in the dollar, people will generally continue holding currencies with high yields," said <PERSON>Mr. Minnaar</PERSON> of <LOCATION>Chase Manhattan</LOCATION>. 

   Nonetheless, traders and others remain nervous, wondering at what level the <ORGANIZATION>Bank of England</ORGANIZATION> might intervene to stop sterling's rise. 
Many believe it could be around <MONEY>3.10 marks</MONEY>. 
"They will intervene at some time," said <PERSON>Mr. De</PERSON> La Salle of <ORGANIZATION>National Westminster Bank</ORGANIZATION>. 
"But only to smooth it out, when sterling rises too rapidly. 
They will let the pound reach its own equilibrium." 

   Traders also expect next <DATE>Tuesday</DATE>'s announcement of <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION>'s budget for the fiscal year beginning <DATE>April 5</DATE> to signal the <LOCATION>U.K.</LOCATION> government's deficit targets, tax program and overall borrowing needs. 

   In other activity, the mark surged against its weaker counterparts -- particularly the French franc and Italian lira -- in the exchange-rate mechanism of the <ORGANIZATION>European Monetary System</ORGANIZATION>, of which the pound is not a member. 
Traders said the advance began when the <LOCATION>Banque</LOCATION> de <LOCATION>France</LOCATION> declined to quote prices on the so-called mark-franc cross rate to commercial banks. 

   Dealers read that as a decision not to defend the French currency, and investors who had sold marks for higher-yielding francs began unwinding their short mark positions. 
Others noted apprehension over the two-part French presidential elections <DATE>April 24</DATE> and <DATE>May 8</DATE>. 
One dealer mentioned a market rumor of a large speculative order to buy marks and sell francs based on a belief that as-yet-undeclared French President <PERSON>Francois Mitterrand</PERSON> wouldn't run. 

   The franc fell to just above its preset floor against the mark in the <ORGANIZATION>EMS</ORGANIZATION>, raising speculation about whether the joint-float of eight continental currencies would have to be realigned before the French elections. 

   "I don't think anything will happen," said <PERSON>Roberto Bianchi</PERSON>, a vice president with <ORGANIZATION>Union Bank of Switzerland</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Zurich</LOCATION>. 
"But uncertainty increases as we get closer to the (French) election." 

   Meanwhile, traders attributed the dollar's stability against the yen to Japanese interest in keeping the dollar from falling further before the end of <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>'s fiscal year at month's end. 
If the yen rises more than <PERCENT>15%</PERCENT> from <DATE>April 1</DATE> to <DATE>March 31</DATE>, big institutional investors in <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION> could be forced to revalue their dollar portfolios and possibly have large losses. 

   On the <ORGANIZATION>Commodity Exchange</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>, gold for current delivery settled at <MONEY>$443.20</MONEY> an ounce, up <MONEY>$7</MONEY>. 
Volume was very heavy at an estimated six million ounces. 

   Gold was quoted at <MONEY>$442.05</MONEY> an ounce in early trading <DATE>Friday</DATE> in <LOCATION>Hong Kong</LOCATION>. 

