<HL> Currency Markets:
Dollar Is Mixed
After Touching
A 5-Month Low
---
Loss Against Mark Is Cut;
Officials Call Slight Fall
By U.S. Unit Acceptable
---
By Charles W. Stevens
Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal</HL>
<DD> 10/27/87</DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO>
<IN> EUROP JAPAN CANDA FREST
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
FOREIGN-EXCHANGE MARKETS (FRX)
PRECIOUS METALS, STONES, GOLD, SILVER (PCS)
COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD) </IN>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was mixed yesterday after rebounding from a sell-off in <LOCATION>Europe</LOCATION> that sent it to a five-month low against the West German mark. 

   Meanwhile, West German monetary officials said they wouldn't intervene to block a further slight decline in the dollar's value. 
The remarks by the officials, who didn't want to be identified, tend to support the belief of many currency traders that officials of major industrial nations have lowered the range of dollar exchange rates that they would find acceptable. 

   One West German official described the dollar's fall in <LOCATION>Europe</LOCATION> yesterday as "only a slight weakening, within reasonable ranges." 
He said, "No one here has much trouble with these levels." 

   Traders attributed the dollar's recovery yesterday largely to buying aimed at taking profits on oversold positions. 
But some said a repatriation of <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> funds that had been invested in the <LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION> stock market helped push the currency up against the Japanese yen. 

   Because of falling <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> interest rates, however, there was little optimism among traders about the dollar's outlook. 

   "The interest-rate differential is working against the dollar," <PERSON>Albert Soria</PERSON>, vice president, foreign exchange, for <ORGANIZATION>Swiss Bank Corp.</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>, said. 
He was referring to the narrowing of the spread between yields on <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> and foreign instruments that had favored dollar-denominated investments. 

   As was the case a week earlier when <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> stocks suffered a record <PERCENT>22.6%</PERCENT> decline, the dollar didn't react negatively yesterday as Wall Street took another pounding. 
While the Dow Jones Industrial Average was plunging 156.83 points, the dollar was climbing back from its intraday lows reached in European trading. 

   The dollar's initial fall yesterday was based on an assumption among currency traders that the <ORGANIZATION>U.S. Federal Reserve</ORGANIZATION> will maintain downward pressure on interest rates as long as the economy faces the threat of a collapsing stock market. 

   "With the stock market sell-off, there's no way the <ORGANIZATION>Fed</ORGANIZATION> is going to use short-term interest rates to defend the dollar," <PERSON>Jim O'Neill</PERSON>, financial markets economist in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> for <ORGANIZATION>Marine Midland Bank</ORGANIZATION>, said. 

   Lower interest rates tend to make dollar-denominated investments less attractive and to decrease demand for the dollar. 
There also is significant doubt that the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION>'s major allies would ease their rates in step with the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION>, meaning that dollar investments' yield advantage would be further threatened. 

   The Swiss franc benefited most from the early dollar selling yesterday, as investors headed for the Swiss bond market, <PERSON>Mr. Soria</PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION>Swiss Bank Corp.</ORGANIZATION> said. 

   "It's strictly a flight to quality; I don't think investors want to go into any stock market right now," he said. 

   About midway through the European trading day, the dollar stood at <MONEY>1.4565 Swiss francs</MONEY>, down <PERCENT>0.9%</PERCENT> from 1.4693 late <DATE>Friday</DATE> in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>. 
Against the West German currency, it was at a five-month low of <MONEY>1.7650 marks</MONEY>, down <PERCENT>0.7%</PERCENT> from 1.7780 late <DATE>Friday</DATE>. 

   In late <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> trading yesterday, after traders bought the currency to cover short, or oversold, positions, the dollar was quoted at <MONEY>1.4656 Swiss francs</MONEY> and <MONEY>1.7775 marks</MONEY>. 

   The dollar's performance against the yen was a slightly different story and involved more than profit-taking by currency speculators. 

   The <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> currency recovered yesterday to stand at <MONEY>142.50 yen</MONEY> late in the <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> day, up <PERCENT>0.5%</PERCENT> from 141.73 late <DATE>Friday</DATE>. 
Among those selling yen to buy dollars were <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> mutual funds repatriating proceeds from sales on the <LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION> stock market, according to <PERSON>Eishi Wakabayashi</PERSON>, head of currency and bond trading at <ORGANIZATION>Nippon Kangyo Kakumaru International Inc.</ORGANIZATION>, the <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> unit of a Japanese investment house. 

   "They think the <LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION> (stock) market is more overvalued than <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>'s, and there's a sense that they'd rather take their business home," he said. 

   The dollar also firmed against the British pound as sterling slipped to <MONEY>$1.6845</MONEY> from <MONEY>$1.6850</MONEY>. 
Traders said the <ORGANIZATION>Bank of England</ORGANIZATION> intervened in European trading to buy dollars against sterling. 
The central bank declined to comment, but British monetary sources confirmed the purchases. 

   Traders said they believe the intervention was intended primarily to weaken the pound against the mark. 
For trade reasons, the sterling-mark relationship is currently more important to British authorities than the dollar rate. 
For some time, the <ORGANIZATION>Bank of England</ORGANIZATION> has sought to keep the pound below <MONEY>3.00 marks</MONEY>. 
The pound eased yesterday to <MONEY>2.9942 marks</MONEY> from 2.9959. 

   The West German <ORGANIZATION>Bundesbank</ORGANIZATION> bought <MONEY>$22.7 million</MONEY> at the <LOCATION>Frankfurt</LOCATION> foreign exchange fixing yesterday, but this wasn't considered a sizable intervention. 
There were no reports of West German central bank activity in the open market. 

   Meanwhile, <ORGANIZATION>Banque Nationale de Belgique</ORGANIZATION> sold a substantial amount of marks and bought Belgian francs at the <LOCATION>Brussels</LOCATION> foreign exchange fixing to try to shore up the Belgian currency. 

   On the <ORGANIZATION>Commodity Exchange</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>, gold for current delivery rose <MONEY>$2.80</MONEY> an ounce to <MONEY>$476.20</MONEY> in brisk trading. 
Estimated volume was 4.5 million ounces. 

