<HL> Currency Markets: Pound Rises With Oil Prices, Mideast Tension --- British Currency Surpasses $1.90 for a 6-Year High; Dollar Generally Mixed </HL>
<AUTHOR> Charles W. Stevens (WSJ Staff) </AUTHOR>
<SO> </SO>
<CO> EUROP FREST JAPAN CANDA </CO>
<IN> MON PCS CMD FRX </IN>
<TEXT>
   The British pound climbed to a six-year high, spurred by increased oil prices and new hostilities in the <LOCATION>Middle East</LOCATION>. 

   The dollar was narrowly mixed against other major currencies. 
Traders said the dollar probably would have had a broad decline if not for the Mideast developments, which fueled interest in the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> currency as a haven for international investors. 

   "Most people think the dollar is going down because of the trade deficit," <PERSON>Ian M. Spence</PERSON>, chief foreign exchange dealer at <ORGANIZATION>Manufacturers Hanover Trust Co.</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>, said. 
However, he said, "Money seems to come to the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> during times of trouble. 
It's the old safe haven theory." 

   The investor concerns were triggered by a <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> strike against two Iranian oil platforms and several Iranian vessels in the <LOCATION>Persian Gulf</LOCATION> <DATE>yesterday</DATE>, in retaliation for last week's mine attack that crippled a <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> frigate. 
The events added to market nervousness about the region that already had been stirred by the Israeli-Palestinian clashes in the occupied <LOCATION>West Bank</LOCATION>. 

   Because <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> is an oil exporter, the pound strengthened as the worsening <LOCATION>Middle East</LOCATION> tensions lifted oil prices. 
The pound climbed to <MONEY>$1.9055</MONEY> in intraday dealings, its highest level since <DATE>January 1982</DATE>. 
In late <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> trading, the pound stood at <MONEY>$1.9005</MONEY>, up <PERCENT>0.6%</PERCENT> from <MONEY>$1.8895</MONEY> late <DATE>Friday</DATE>. 

   The pound's sharpest gain came against the yen because of the vulnerability of the Japanese economy to any surge in oil prices, traders said. 
<LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION> imports nearly all its petroleum. 
The pound climbed <PERCENT>0.8%</PERCENT> to <MONEY>236.16 yen</MONEY> from 234.26. 

   Traders said sterling also continues to benefit from relatively high British interest rates. 
Sterling-denominated three-month Eurodeposits yielded <PERCENT>7 7/8%</PERCENT> yesterday, compared with <PERCENT>4 1/16%</PERCENT> for a similar yen-denominated investment. 
Although <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION>'s interest-rate advantage over the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> has narrowed recently, traders said sterling investments continue to be significantly more attractive. 

   For these reasons, sterling "is the strongest of the currencies right now and looks like it still wants to go higher," said <PERSON>John J. McCarthy</PERSON>, vice president, foreign exchange, at <ORGANIZATION>Irving Trust Co.</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>. 

   According to traders, the <ORGANIZATION>U.S. Federal Reserve</ORGANIZATION> intervened to sell sterling against dollars yesterday, presumably on behalf of the <ORGANIZATION>Bank of England</ORGANIZATION>. 

   In other dealings, the dollar firmed to <MONEY>124.26 yen</MONEY> from 123.98 and eased to <MONEY>1.6605 marks</MONEY> from 1.6625. 

   In midmorning trading in <LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION> <DATE>Tuesday</DATE>, the dollar was quoted at <MONEY>124.35 yen</MONEY>. 

   On the <ORGANIZATION>Commodity Exchange</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>, gold for current delivery rose <MONEY>$3.40</MONEY> an ounce to <MONEY>$459.40</MONEY> in moderate trading. 
Estimated volume was three million ounces. 

