<HL> Currency Markets: U.K. Rules Out Intervention To Limit Pound --- Thatcher's Speech Removes Trader Concern; Sterling Rises 1.3% Against Dollar </HL>
<AUTHOR> Peter Torday and Charles W. Stevens (WSJ Staff) </AUTHOR>
<SO> </SO>
<CO> EUROP JAPAN CANDA FREST </CO>
<IN> MON PCS CMD FRX </IN>
<TEXT>
   The British pound's rally continued yesterday as Prime Minister <PERSON>Margaret Thatcher</PERSON> said the government won't intervene to halt sterling's rise. 

   <PERSON>Mrs. Thatcher</PERSON>'s statement to <LOCATION>Parliament</LOCATION> was chiefly intended to clarify British monetary policy. 
But it removed concerns among currency traders that the <ORGANIZATION>Bank of England</ORGANIZATION> might attempt to put a lid on sterling's value by selling pounds in the foreign exchange market. 

   With those fears doused, and with the attraction of relatively high British interest rates, traders renewed their rush into the currency. 
The pound climbed to <MONEY>$1.8424</MONEY> in late <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> dealings, up <PERCENT>1.3%</PERCENT> from <MONEY>$1.8182</MONEY> <DATE>Monday</DATE>. 
Meanwhile, the dollar eased against other European currencies but gained slightly against the yen. 

   The pound also advanced <PERCENT>0.8%</PERCENT> to 3.0720 West German marks, from 3.0488. 
From <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION>'s perspective, the sterling-mark exchange rate is of more importance than the pound's dollar value because most British trade is with <LOCATION>West Germany</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Western Europe</LOCATION>, where many currencies are linked to the mark. 

   Until this week, <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> had for more than a year used interest rates and foreign exchange market intervention to maintain the pound's value below three marks to encourage exports. 
A weaker pound makes British products less expensive for foreign consumers. 

   The decision to let the pound rise above three marks signaled that the British government is more concerned about fighting inflation than spurring exports. 
"Excessive intervention," <PERSON>Mrs. Thatcher</PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION>House of Commons</ORGANIZATION> yesterday, "would lead to inflation, and that is no part of our policy." 
She added that a cut in British banks' base lending rates, currently <PERCENT>9%</PERCENT>, also would be inflationary. 

   Selling sterling through intervention tends to be inflationary by increasing the money supply. 
Lowering interest rates would be an alternative way to reduce demand for sterling by lessening the appeal of holding the currency. 
But lower interest rates might also be inflationary by overstimulating the already robust British economy. 

   <PERSON>Mrs. Thatcher</PERSON>'s remarks reflect the government's deepening concern about possibly inflationary pay settlements in <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION>. 
But her statement carries implications stretching beyond British shores. 
Market economists note that the shift in British monetary policy may undercut the dollar's stability. 

   "The second biggest buyer of dollars in <DATE>1987</DATE> is saying: 'We're not doing it any more,'" said <PERSON>Jim O'Neill</PERSON>, financial markets economist at <ORGANIZATION>Marine Midland Bank</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>. 
"Can you imagine if the Japanese said the same thing?" 

   British government officials yesterday declined to say whether they informed <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION> about their move away from large-scale intervention. 
But <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION>'s new policy probably will hold center stage today when senior officials of the 11 leading industrial nations meet in <LOCATION>Paris</LOCATION> to review the global outlook for currency stability. 

   In <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION>Treasury</ORGANIZATION> wouldn't comment on <PERSON>Mrs. Thatcher</PERSON>'s decision. 
But privately, administration officials were interpreting it as a British and European policy matter that doesn't imply any change in <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION>'s willingness to support the dollar under the <DATE>Dec. 22</DATE> agreement by the <ORGANIZATION>Group of Seven</ORGANIZATION> countries. 

   "We have no reason to think the <LOCATION>United Kingdom</LOCATION> has changed its policy on the dollar in any way," an administration official declared. 
"All of the <ORGANIZATION>G-7</ORGANIZATION> governments continue to support the <DATE>Dec. 22</DATE> agreement." 
The official said neither <PERSON>Mrs. Thatcher</PERSON> nor Chancellor of the Exchequer <PERSON>Nigel Lawson</PERSON> had contacted the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> government to communicate any change in their willingness to back the dollar. 

   In the <DATE>Dec. 22</DATE> communique the seven nations declared the dollar had fallen enough. 
And in the ensuing weeks, they intervened heavily in currency markets to prop it up against the Japanese yen and German mark. 
<LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> isn't as important in these endeavors as the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>, or <LOCATION>Germany</LOCATION>. 
And the dollar's value against the pound isn't considered a vital measure of currency stability by <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> officials. 

   In other foreign exchange activity, the dollar fell against most major European currencies, slipping, for example, to <MONEY>1.6674 marks</MONEY> from 1.6768. 
The dollar firmed against the Japanese yen to 127.85 from 127.79. 

   The dollar was quoted at <MONEY>127.95 yen</MONEY> in early <LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION> trading <DATE>Wednesday</DATE>. 

   On the <ORGANIZATION>Commodity Exchange</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>, gold for current delivery fell <MONEY>$2</MONEY> an ounce to <MONEY>$435.30</MONEY> in moderate trading. 
The estimated volume was 2.5 million ounces. 

