<TEXT>
   The dollar was only slightly changed but mostly lower in lazy pre-holiday trading. 

   The currency kept to one of its narrowest daily ranges of the year. 
Such restrained activity may well continue for the rest of the <DATE>summer</DATE>, some dealers said. 

   "There's nothing at the moment to indicate a breakout of this market," <PERSON>Alfred Driever</PERSON>, vice president, foreign exchange, at <ORGANIZATION>Salomon Brothers Inc.</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>, said. 

   From the beginning of yesterday's trading in <LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION> through late <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> dealings, the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> currency crawled between 1.8195 and 1.8295 West German marks. 
Late in the day in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>, it stood at <MONEY>1.8278 marks</MONEY>, barely higher than 1.8273 late <DATE>Tuesday</DATE>. 

   <PERSON>John W. Baker</PERSON>, chief foreign exchange trader for <ORGANIZATION>Bank Julius Baer &amp; Co.</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>, said the dollar could remain trapped between 1.81 and <MONEY>1.84 marks</MONEY> for the rest of the <DATE>summer</DATE>. 
"We have a <DATE>summer</DATE> trading range and the <DATE>summer</DATE> blues," he said. 

   Against other currencies, the dollar inched lower to 146.80 Japanese yen from 146.93 <DATE>Tuesday</DATE>. 
The British pound climbed to <MONEY>$1.6170</MONEY> from <MONEY>$1.6138</MONEY>. 

   In early trading <DATE>today</DATE> in <LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION>, the dollar was quoted at <MONEY>146.92 yen</MONEY>. 

   Despite the dollar's recent stability, negative sentiment on the currency remains strong in the market. 

   "The fundamentals point to a lower dollar," <PERSON>Mr. Baker</PERSON> said, referring to the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION>'s trade and budget deficits and sluggish economy. 
"But there's no point to selling the dollar. 
The upside is limited, but the downside is limited. 
People are hesitant to take large positions when there's no direction to the market." 

   Salomon's <PERSON>Mr. Driever</PERSON> said: "Most people believe the (eventual) push will be on the downside rather than the upside. 
But that's irrelevant right now because we're just range-trading." 

   In <LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION>Bank of Japan</ORGANIZATION> Governor <PERSON>Satoshi Sumita</PERSON> said the central bank will have to watch exchange rates carefully despite the dollar's recent stability. 
<PERSON>Mr. Sumita</PERSON> told a news conference that because the large trade imbalance between the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION> remains basically unchanged despite a slight improvement, "we cannot keep our eyes off the exchange rates." 

   On the <ORGANIZATION>Commodity Exchange</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>, gold for current delivery fell <MONEY>$2.50</MONEY> an ounce to <MONEY>$446.90</MONEY> in moderate trading. 
Estimated volume was three million ounces. 

