<HL> Currency Markets:
Dollar Gains
As Tax Proposal
Weakens Mark
---
Bonn's Plan for Levy Helps
U.S. Currency to Rise
In Thin Holiday Trading
---
By Charles W. Stevens
Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal</HL>
<DD> 10/13/87</DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO>
<IN> EUROP FREST CANDA JAPAN
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
FOREIGN-EXCHANGE MARKETS (FRX)
PRECIOUS METALS, STONES, GOLD, SILVER (PCS)
COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD) </IN>
<TEXT>
   The dollar firmed in sparse holiday trading on <DATE>Friday</DATE>'s news that <LOCATION>West Germany</LOCATION> will impose a <PERCENT>10%</PERCENT> withholding tax on most income from investments and bank deposits. 

   Trading was all but nonexistent in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> because of the <LOCATION>Columbus</LOCATION> Day holiday, which also curtailed volume in European currency markets. 

   The thin market and traders' caution ahead of tomorrow's <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> report on the <DATE>August</DATE> trade balance meant few major dollar positions were created. 
Attention focused instead on trading among other currencies, in which the West German mark generally weakened because of the proposed withholding tax. 

   Traders said such a levy, which <LOCATION>Bonn</LOCATION> proposes to enact in <DATE>1989</DATE>, would divert investment from <LOCATION>West Germany</LOCATION> and from mark-denominated assets to <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Switzerland</LOCATION> and the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> 

   In <LOCATION>London</LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION>Bank of England</ORGANIZATION> sold a small amount of British pounds in the foreign exchange market to try to hold sterling below <MONEY>3.00 marks</MONEY>, dealers said. 

   The British central bank entered the market with the pound trading at <MONEY>2.9990 marks</MONEY>, a dealer said. 
Because of the shallowness of yesterday's market, the intervention easily pushed the pound back down to <MONEY>2.9968 marks</MONEY>. 
But in the sparse price quotes posted late in the <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> trading day, sterling rebounded to 3.001, compared with 2.9948 late <DATE>Friday</DATE> in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>. 

   Although the <ORGANIZATION>Bank of England</ORGANIZATION>, as usual, wouldn't comment on the reported intervention, monetary sources confirmed the activity. 

   The dollar was quoted at <MONEY>1.8153 marks</MONEY> in late <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> trading, compared with 1.8103 late <DATE>Friday</DATE>. 
The <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> currency also firmed to 143.90 Japanese yen from 143.68, while the pound eased to <MONEY>$1.6530</MONEY> from <MONEY>$1.6543</MONEY>. 

   The <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> currency was trading at <MONEY>142.95 yen</MONEY> in early <LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION> activity today. 

   The dollar began yesterday by strengthening in Asian markets, helped by a report that <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>'s trade surplus narrowed to <MONEY>$7.43 billion</MONEY> in <DATE>September</DATE> from <MONEY>$8.95 billion</MONEY> a year earlier. 
Although the surplus was wider than the <MONEY>$5.15 billion</MONEY> in the previous month, <DATE>September</DATE> was the fifth consecutive month in which <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>'s trade surplus has narrowed from a year earlier. 

   Many market participants remain pessimistic about tomorrow's <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> trade report. 

   <PERSON>Paul S. Chertkow</PERSON>, director of currency research at <ORGANIZATION>Hoare Govett</ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION>London</LOCATION> unit of <ORGANIZATION>Security Pacific Corp.</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>Los Angeles</LOCATION>, said the dollar will fall to <MONEY>1.79 marks</MONEY> and <MONEY>141 yen</MONEY> this month if the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> trade deficit is <MONEY>$13 billion</MONEY> or wider. 
The <DATE>July</DATE> gap was a record <MONEY>$16.47 billion</MONEY>. 

   "A <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> deficit in the order of <MONEY>$13 billion</MONEY> would still leave the cumulative deficit in the first eight months of the year some <PERCENT>2.5%</PERCENT> higher than in the same period of <DATE>1986</DATE>," he said. 

   <PERSON>David Rumsey</PERSON>, a <LOCATION>London</LOCATION> trader for New York-based <ORGANIZATION>Citicorp</ORGANIZATION>, said, "People are preparing themselves for bad news." 
He cited a survey of economists last week in which the consensus forecast was for a <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> trade deficit of <MONEY>$14.3 billion</MONEY>. 

   <PERSON>Mr. Chertkow</PERSON> said the narrowing Japanese surplus shouldn't lead to optimism about the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> report. 

   "There is no statistical correlation between the monthly trade data of the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> and that of <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>," he said. 

   On the <ORGANIZATION>Commodity Exchange</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>, gold for current delivery fell <MONEY>20 cents</MONEY> an ounce to <MONEY>$461.70</MONEY> in light trading. 
Estimated volume was 1.3 million ounces. 

   Gold was quoted at <MONEY>$461.75</MONEY> an ounce in early trading <DATE>today</DATE> in <LOCATION>Hong Kong</LOCATION>. 

