<HL> Currency Markets: Pound Keeps Going Up Even as Banks In Britain Cut Base Rates Half a Point </HL>
<AUTHOR> Barbara Toman (WSJ Staff) </AUTHOR>
<SO> </SO>
<CO> EUROP CANDA FREST JAPAN </CO>
<IN> MON FRX PCS CMD </IN>
<DATELINE> LONDON  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain seems to be losing the battle to curb its currency. 

   Although British base rates fell half a point to <PERCENT>8%</PERCENT> <DATE>Friday</DATE> -- their lowest level in a decade -- the pound persevered to close higher against the mark and unchanged against the dollar. 
Foreign exchange markets probably will be quiet early this week, before the <ORGANIZATION>Group of Seven</ORGANIZATION> finance ministers meet in <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION>. 
But after that, economists here expect sterling to resume its rise, pushing toward <MONEY>$1.90</MONEY> and 3.15-3.20 marks. 

   By <DATE>today</DATE>, "We'll all be wondering what (the base-rate cut) has achieved," <PERSON>Graham Turner</PERSON>, an economist at <ORGANIZATION>Warburg Securities</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>London</LOCATION>, predicted <DATE>Friday</DATE>. 
"And the answer is, not much. 
Cutting base rates will do nothing to divert the current bullish sentiment from sterling." 

   <DATE>Friday</DATE>'s interest rate cut followed apparently coordinated, and largely unsuccessful, intervention by the <ORGANIZATION>Bank of England</ORGANIZATION> and the West German central bank <DATE>earlier last week</DATE> to buy dollars for pounds. 
Sterling's continued resistance to downward pressure is a blow against <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION>'s efforts to maintain stable exchange rates. 
And sharp cuts in interest rates renew worries about a further deterioration in <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION>'s widening current-account deficit. 

   Chancellor of the Exchequer <PERSON>Nigel Lawson</PERSON> surprised markets <DATE>Friday</DATE> by directing banks to cut their base rates to <PERCENT>8%</PERCENT>. 
The previous day sterling had surged to a two-year high in <LOCATION>London</LOCATION> of <MONEY>3.13 marks</MONEY> despite the apparent intervention by central banks. 
When trading opened <DATE>Friday</DATE>, the pound continued to rise, quickly edging above <MONEY>3.14 marks</MONEY>. 

   Later that morning, the <ORGANIZATION>Bank of England</ORGANIZATION> lowered its money market intervention rate 3/8 point to <PERCENT>8%</PERCENT>, prompting <ORGANIZATION>Midland Bank PLC</ORGANIZATION> to announce its base-rate reduction. 
Other leading British banks soon followed. 
Last month, banks decreased base rates to <PERCENT>8 1/2%</PERCENT> from <PERCENT>9%</PERCENT>, reversing a half-point rise <DATE>Feb.1</DATE>. 

   Government officials said they intended the base-rate cut to counteract somewhat the tightening of monetary policy caused by the rising pound. 
Officials said they also wanted to send a decisive signal to investors that the government would prevent the pound rising "unsustainably." 
But despite the effort, sterling closed <DATE>Friday</DATE> at 3.14, up a pfennig from <DATE>Thursday</DATE>. 
The pound rose a little against the dollar, to <MONEY>$1.8755</MONEY> from <MONEY>$1.8720</MONEY>. 

   Sterling remains buoyed by <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION>'s probable strong economic growth this year, its relatively high interest rates compared with <LOCATION>West Germany</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>, and by investors' skepticism over whether the British government will cut interest rates here further. 
"With the fundamentals still in sterling's favor, it remains the currency to be with," said <PERSON>Peter Fellner</PERSON>, an economist at stockbrokers <ORGANIZATION>James Capel &amp; Co</ORGANIZATION>. 

   With sterling rising, inflation doesn't seem a likely result of the downward ratchet in interest rates. 
A bigger worry is a further deterioration in <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION>'s current-account deficit, which stood at <MONEY>#720 million</MONEY> (<MONEY>$1.35 billion</MONEY>) in <DATE>February</DATE> compared with a surplus of <MONEY>#430 million</MONEY> a year earlier. 
The current account tallies a nation's trade in goods, services and certain unilateral transfers. 
A further decline in <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION>'s current-account deficit could occur if higher demand, resulting from lower interest rates, sucks in more imports. 

