<HL> Currency Markets: Profit-Taking Ends Sterling's Eight-Day Rise --- Dollar Strengthens Widely But Drops Against Yen; U.K. Budget Due Today </HL>
<AUTHOR> Charles W. Stevens (WSJ Staff) </AUTHOR>
<SO> </SO>
<CO> EUROP FREST JAPAN CANDA </CO>
<IN> MON PCS CMD FRX </IN>
<TEXT>
   The pound lost ground for the first time in eight trading days yesterday as dealers sold sterling to take profits on its <PERCENT>5%</PERCENT> rise since <DATE>March 3</DATE>. 

   Traders said sterling's weakness spilled over to other European currencies, allowing the dollar to strengthen across a wide front. 

   The dollar eased against the yen, however. 
Unlike the European currencies, the yen didn't benefit indirectly from the pound's recent strength, and therefore, the Japanese currency wasn't pressured by yesterday's selling of sterling, traders said. 

   The profit-taking on sterling positions yesterday came on the eve of today's release of the <LOCATION>U.K.</LOCATION> budget for the fiscal year beginning in <DATE>April</DATE>, and a budget speech to Parliament by Chancellor of the Exchequer <PERSON>Nigel Lawson</PERSON>. 
The budget is expected to show a surplus for the year in addition to as much as <MONEY>#4 billion</MONEY> (<MONEY>$7.43 billion</MONEY>) in tax cuts. 

   "The good news is out," said <PERSON>Richard E. Witten</PERSON>, vice president, foreign exchange at <ORGANIZATION>Goldman, Sachs &amp; Co.</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>. 
People already know "how optimistic <PERSON>Lawson</PERSON>'s budget message will be and there was a lot of profit-taking," he said. 

   The pound was quoted at <MONEY>$1.8515</MONEY> in late <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> trading <DATE>Monday</DATE>, down <PERCENT>0.3%</PERCENT> from <MONEY>$1.8565</MONEY> <DATE>Friday</DATE>. 

   In other trading, the dollar climbed <PERCENT>0.3%</PERCENT> to 1.6650 West German marks, from 1.6600 <DATE>Friday</DATE>, and slipped <PERCENT>0.4%</PERCENT> to <MONEY>126.90 yen</MONEY>, from 127.36. 

   In <LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION>, the dollar opened <DATE>Tuesday</DATE> at <MONEY>127.04 yen</MONEY>, down from <MONEY>127.23 yen</MONEY> <DATE>Monday</DATE> in <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>. 

   Trading was subdued by anticipation of the British budget news <DATE>today</DATE> and <DATE>Thursday</DATE>'s release of <LOCATION>January U.S.</LOCATION> merchandise trade data. 
Market participants generally expect the trade report to show that the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> trade deficit widened to between <MONEY>$13 billion</MONEY> and <MONEY>$14 billion</MONEY>, from <MONEY>$12.2 billion</MONEY> in <DATE>December</DATE>. 
Expectations for a deeper trade deficit will keep downward pressure on the dollar for the rest of the week, traders said. 

   In the event of a better-than-expected trade report, many dealers believe the dollar's upside potential is limited. 
<PERSON>Keiichi Udagawa</PERSON>, chief trader at <ORGANIZATION>Bank of Tokyo Ltd.</ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> agency, said any dollar recovery will trigger existing sell orders, by Japanese exporters in particular, which would cool any dollar rally. 

   On the <ORGANIZATION>Commodity Exchange</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>, gold for current delivery rose <MONEY>60 cents</MONEY> an ounce to <MONEY>$441.90</MONEY> in moderate trading. 
The estimated volume was 2.5 million ounces. 

