<HL> Currency Markets:
Dollar Is Lower
On Intervention
By Bundesbank
---
West German Move Viewed
As Effort to Keep Rates
Stable Under Paris Pact
---
By Charles W. Stevens
Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal</HL>
<DD> 08/06/87</DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO>
<IN> EUROP JAPAN FREST CANDA
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
FOREIGN-EXCHANGE MARKETS (FRX)
PRECIOUS METALS, STONES, GOLD, SILVER (PCS)
COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD) </IN>
<TEXT>
   The dollar dropped back in foreign exchange trading in response to intervention by the West German central bank. 

   Despite the <ORGANIZATION>Bundesbank</ORGANIZATION>'s dollar sales, traders said, simmering tensions in the <LOCATION>Middle East</LOCATION> probably will keep the upward pressure on the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> currency. 

   A <ORGANIZATION>Bundesbank</ORGANIZATION> spokesman in <LOCATION>Frankfurt</LOCATION> confirmed that the central bank sold dollars yesterday after the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> currency came off an intraday high of 1.8890 West German marks. 
That represents a high-water mark for the dollar in its current rally sparked by fears of a widening <LOCATION>Persian Gulf</LOCATION> conflict. 

   The dollar climbed to 6 1/2-month highs early this week as investors sought the currency after <LOCATION>Iran</LOCATION> threatened to expand its war against <ORGANIZATION>Iraq</ORGANIZATION> to include other Mideast nations and the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> 
The Iranian threat followed the deaths of rioting Iranian pilgrims in <LOCATION>Saudi Arabia</LOCATION> <DATE>Friday</DATE>. 

   In late <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> trading yesterday, the dollar stood at <MONEY>1.8804 marks</MONEY>, compared with 1.8885 late <DATE>Tuesday</DATE>. 
It also fell to 150.82 Japanese yen from 151.68, and the British pound climbed to <MONEY>$1.5797</MONEY> from <MONEY>$1.5735</MONEY>. 

   In early <LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION> trading today, the dollar was quoted at <MONEY>150.70 yen</MONEY>. 

   Market participants generally viewed yesterday's <ORGANIZATION>Bundesbank</ORGANIZATION> intervention in the context of <DATE>February</DATE>'s <LOCATION>Paris</LOCATION> agreement between the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> and its major allies to keep exchange rates stable. 
Periodic intervention since that agreement has led many traders to believe that the major central banks aim to keep the dollar roughly between 1.80 and <MONEY>1.90 marks</MONEY>. 

   Other market speculation holds that the central banks only want to dull any sharp spikes in exchange-rate movements. 

   "At the moment, they're putting a cap on the dollar at 1.8850 (marks)," <PERSON>Yani M.A. Budiman</PERSON>, vice president, corporate foreign exchange, at <ORGANIZATION>Chemical Bank</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>, said. 
However, he said, the dollar will remain supported "as long as tensions in the <LOCATION>Mideast</LOCATION> continue." 

   <PERSON>Martin Rieben</PERSON>, vice president, foreign exchange, for <ORGANIZATION>Swiss Bank Corp.</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>, said "the dollar will slowly go up" even if central bank intervention against the currency is resumed. 

   "It's the <LOCATION>Middle East</LOCATION>, it's the uncertainty. 
We don't know what's cooking, but we smell it everywhere," <PERSON>Mr. Rieben</PERSON> said. 
"I feel secure if I have a few dollars in my pocket." 

   The chief trader at one bank with close central bank ties speculated that <LOCATION>West Germany</LOCATION> may have had its own reasons for intervening. 
The <ORGANIZATION>Bundesbank</ORGANIZATION>, along with the <ORGANIZATION>U.S. Federal Reserve</ORGANIZATION> and other central banks, bought large amounts of dollars this <DATE>spring</DATE> to halt a steep dive in the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> currency's value. 
In selling dollars yesterday, the trader said, the <ORGANIZATION>Bundesbank</ORGANIZATION> could have registered a sizable foreign exchange profit. 

   "I think they'd be thrilled if the dollar went higher," he said. 

   In addition, he said, any <ORGANIZATION>Bundesbank</ORGANIZATION> move to sell dollars and buy marks would help <LOCATION>West Germany</LOCATION>'s efforts to control its rapidly expanding money supply. 

   On the <ORGANIZATION>Commodity Exchange</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>, gold for current delivery fell <MONEY>$10.80</MONEY> an ounce to <MONEY>$466.80</MONEY> in brisk trading. 
Estimated volume was 5.8 million ounces. 

   Gold was quoted at <MONEY>$467.85</MONEY> an ounce in early trading <DATE>today</DATE> in <LOCATION>Hong Kong</LOCATION>. 

