<HL> Currency Markets:
Dollar Is Mixed
In Thin Trading;
Pound Advances
---
Poll Result Aids British Unit
As Quiet Market Awaits
Start of 5-Nation Talks
---
By Charles W. Stevens
Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal</HL>
<DD> 04/07/87</DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO>
<IN> EUROP JAPAN FREST CANDA
FOREIGN-EXCHANGE MARKETS (FRX)
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
PRECIOUS METALS, STONES, GOLD, SILVER (PCS)
COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD) </IN>
<TEXT>
   Public opinion polls in <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> that showed the ruling <ORGANIZATION>Conservative Party</ORGANIZATION> widening its lead over its rivals caused the British pound to rally in otherwise dull foreign-exchange trading yesterday. 

   The dollar was narrowly mixed in thin trading, and traders said the market could be quiet for the rest of the week while finance ministers from major industrial nations meet in <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION>. 
They cautioned that the calm could be disturbed at any time, however, by leaks or disclosures about the talks. 

   The <ORGANIZATION>Bank of England</ORGANIZATION> was rumored to have stepped in to limit the pound's advance yesterday by selling sterling and buying dollars and West German marks. 
In late <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> trading, the pound stood at <MONEY>$1.6183</MONEY>, up <PERCENT>0.4%</PERCENT> from <MONEY>$1.6120</MONEY> <DATE>Friday</DATE>. 
Sterling also rose against the West German currency to <MONEY>2.9547 marks</MONEY> from 2.9416. 
In intraday trading, the pound reached as high as <MONEY>$1.6240</MONEY> and <MONEY>2.96 marks</MONEY>, traders said. 

   In addition to the British opinion polls published in several major newspapers <DATE>Sunday</DATE> and yesterday, traders said, <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION>'s relatively high interest rates continue to help buoy the pound. 

   Most of the foreign-exchange market, meanwhile, is clinging to a bearish view on the dollar as officials from the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>West Germany</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>France</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> prepare for talks tomorrow. 
The <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> currency's recent fall against most other major currencies presumably will figure prominently in the discussions, which may also include finance officials from <LOCATION>Canada</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Italy</LOCATION>. 

   "When I look at the (<LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION>) trade deficit, there's no doubt in my mind that the dollar has to go lower," <PERSON>Frank Pusateri</PERSON>, assistant vice president and senior corporate trader at <ORGANIZATION>Bank of Boston</ORGANIZATION>, said. 
He said he would be "very surprised" if any major new development comes from the five-nation meeting. 
Next week, he said he expects the dollar to move down to the ranges of 1.77 to <MONEY>1.80 West German marks</MONEY> and 140 to 145 Japanese yen. 

   In late <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> trading yesterday, the dollar stood at <MONEY>1.8258 marks</MONEY>, a slight advance from 1.8248 late <DATE>Friday</DATE>, and at <MONEY>145.93 yen</MONEY>, compared with 146.10 <DATE>Friday</DATE>. 

   The dollar was quoted at <MONEY>145.90 yen</MONEY> in early <LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION> trading <DATE>Tuesday</DATE>. 

   When finance ministers from the major industrial nations met in <LOCATION>Paris</LOCATION> <DATE>Feb. 22</DATE>, they agreed to coordinate measures to stabilize exchange rates. 
Since then, the dollar has fallen <PERCENT>5%</PERCENT> against the yen, even though the five countries' central banks have bought an estimated <MONEY>$10 billion</MONEY> of the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> currency to try to support its value. 
In the same period, by contrast, the dollar has risen <PERCENT>0.4%</PERCENT> against the West German mark. 

   The <ORGANIZATION>Bank of Japan</ORGANIZATION> intervened in the <LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION> market again yesterday, selling yen to buy dollars. 
Japanese Finance Minister <PERSON>Kiichi Miyazawa</PERSON> told a legislative panel in <LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION> that the <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION> talks will probably produce a reaffirmation of the currency-stability accord. 
Traders, meanwhile, said anything short of a reaffirmation would be extremely bearish for the dollar. 

   On the <ORGANIZATION>Commodity Exchange</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>, gold for <DATE>April</DATE> delivery declined <MONEY>$1.20</MONEY> an ounce to <MONEY>$418.50</MONEY> in moderate trading estimated at 3.3 million ounces. 

