<HL> Currency Markets:
Dollar Climbs
As Traders Buy
On U.S. Signals
---
Fed's Recent Intervention
Is Viewed as Reciprocal
For Europe's Rate Cuts
---
By Charles W. Stevens
Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal</HL>
<DD> 12/08/87</DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO>
<IN> EUROP JAPAN FREST CANDA
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
FOREIGN-EXCHANGE MARKETS (FRX)
PRECIOUS METALS, STONES, GOLD, SILVER (PCS)
COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD) </IN>
<TEXT>
   The dollar continued climbing in foreign exchange trading yesterday as dealers weighed the significance of the <ORGANIZATION>U.S. Federal Reserve</ORGANIZATION>'s intervention to support the dollar last week. 

   Neither the <ORGANIZATION>Fed</ORGANIZATION> nor other major central banks were seen intervening in currency markets yesterday, traders said. 
But <DATE>last week</DATE>'s apparently coordinated dollar purchases by the <ORGANIZATION>Fed</ORGANIZATION>, the West German <ORGANIZATION>Bundesbank</ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION>Bank of Japan</ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION>Bank of England</ORGANIZATION> left many dealers with the impression that the major monetary powers were embarking on another period of close cooperation to support the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> currency. 

   "The spirit of the <LOCATION>Louvre</LOCATION> may be coming back again," said <PERSON>Larry Ryan</PERSON>, senior vice president and foreign exchange manager at <ORGANIZATION>European American Bank</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>. 
<PERSON>Mr. Ryan</PERSON> was referring to the currency rate stabilization agreement signed in <LOCATION>Paris</LOCATION> last <DATE>February</DATE>. 

   An article in yesterday's Wall Street Journal reporting a shift in <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> policy toward more emphasis on supporting the dollar also contributed to the currency's strength, traders said. 

   The dollar continued to strengthen more against major European currencies than against the Japanese yen. 
Following last week's interest rate cuts in <LOCATION>Europe</LOCATION>, which made dollar-denominated investments relatively more attractive, Japanese interest rates were left unchanged, maintaining the yield differentials between the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>. 

   In late <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> trading the dollar was quoted at close to its highs of the day. 
The dollar climbed <PERCENT>0.5%</PERCENT> to 1.6783 West German marks, from 1.6695 <DATE>Friday</DATE>, while the British pound eased to <MONEY>$1.7863</MONEY>, from <MONEY>$1.7920</MONEY>. 
Against the Japanese currency, the dollar moved slightly higher to <MONEY>132.97 yen</MONEY>, from 132.50. 
In <LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION> <DATE>Tuesday</DATE>, the dollar opened at <MONEY>133.05 yen</MONEY>, but soon fell below the <MONEY>133 yen</MONEY> level on heavy selling by a Japanese trust bank and conflicting rumors about <DATE>Thursday</DATE>'s <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> <DATE>October</DATE> trade deficit release. 

   Explaining the recent buying interest in dollars, dealers said the <PERSON>Reagan</PERSON> administration has launched a new drive to support the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> currency in response to the European interest rate cuts last week. 
The administration had been pressing for lower interest rates and more stimulative economic policies abroad, especially from <LOCATION>West Germany</LOCATION>. 
Faster growth overseas could spur demand for American products and help narrow the huge <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> trade deficit, the administration reasoned. 

   Traders believe <LOCATION>West Germany</LOCATION> is now getting the cooperation from the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> that it sought in countering the dollar's decline, which makes West German exports costly for Americans and puts stress on the <ORGANIZATION>European Monetary System</ORGANIZATION>, an eight-currency exchange rate mechanism centered around the mark. 

   "The <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION>, as a show of good faith, has gone out to support the dollar, to say 'thank you'" to the West Germans, said <PERSON>Mr. Ryan</PERSON> at <ORGANIZATION>European American Bank</ORGANIZATION>. 
"The dollar's looking like it has a new lease on life," he added. 

   The dollar could get another lift today if speculation yesterday about another lowering of a key interest rate in <LOCATION>West Germany</LOCATION> proves correct. 
The West German central bank, which cut its discount rate last week, may decide to cut more money market rates, making yields on dollar investments more attractive. 
The <ORGANIZATION>Bundesbank</ORGANIZATION> is expected to call for tenders on securities repurchase agreements today. 
The last set of repos were executed at <PERCENT>3.25%</PERCENT> before the discount rate cut. 

   Although sentiment has shifted in favor of the dollar, traders said they remain bearish toward the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> currency. 
Many dealers are watching out for a sell-off of dollars either ahead of or immediately after <DATE>Thursday</DATE>'s <ORGANIZATION>Commerce Department</ORGANIZATION> report on the <DATE>October</DATE> merchandise trade balance. 
The <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> trade deficit remains a big factor in long-term negative outlook for the dollar. 
"Come <DATE>Wednesday</DATE> <TIME>morning</TIME>, you'll probably see interest in taking profits on long (or overbought) dollar positions. 
Old fears of the trade numbers will return," said <PERSON>Leslie A. Puth</PERSON>, a corporate trader at <ORGANIZATION>Banque Indosuez</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>. 

   On the <ORGANIZATION>Commodity Exchange</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>, gold for current delivery fell <MONEY>$1.40</MONEY> an ounce to <MONEY>$481.50</MONEY> in light trading. 
