<HL> Currency Markets: Dollar Declines After Traders Rush to Marks --- Speculation Is Bundesbank Will Raise Interest Rates After a Meeting Today </HL>
<AUTHOR> Peter Goldstein (WSJ Special) </AUTHOR>
<SO> </SO>
<CO> EUROP JAPAN CANDA FREST </CO>
<IN> MON FRX PCS CMD </IN>
<DATELINE> NEW YORK  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A rush to marks ahead of the <ORGANIZATION>Bundesbank</ORGANIZATION>'s central bank council meeting today strengthened the West German currency by three pfennigs against the dollar yesterday. 

   The surge left foreign-exchange traders wondering if the mark's recent decline has come to an end. 

   The mark was boosted by the West German central bank's announcement that a news conference would be held after today's council meeting. 
The announcement invited speculation that the monetary authority would move to raise interest rates then. 
Many economists expect the <ORGANIZATION>Bundesbank</ORGANIZATION> to boost rates because a series of concerted dollar sales by central banks had limited success in swaying bullish sentiments for the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> currency in foreign-exchange markets. 

   In a reversal of recent trading patterns, dealers became increasingly anxious to unload dollars as a succession of events yesterday shifted interest to the mark. 

   The drive started early on when <ORGANIZATION>Bank of Japan</ORGANIZATION> Governor <PERSON>Satoshi Sumita</PERSON>, who has been reticent about criticizing prevailing market-exchange rates, said the mark's decline was "inexplicable and almost unacceptable," and voiced his support for a stable dollar-mark rate. 
His remarks forced the dollar to retreat to <MONEY>1.9020 marks</MONEY> after trading around <MONEY>1.9080 marks</MONEY>. 

   Soon afterward, the <ORGANIZATION>Bundesbank</ORGANIZATION>, along with the Belgian and Swiss central banks, entered the European market to sell dollars for their respective currencies. 
The coordinated action sent the dollar below <MONEY>1.9000 marks</MONEY>, but it bounced back. 

   The <ORGANIZATION>Bundesbank</ORGANIZATION> sold dollars again as <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> trading commenced, and the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> unit again dipped below <MONEY>1.9000 marks</MONEY>. 
Each intervention was confirmed by the central banks. 

   In late afternoon <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> trading, the dollar was at <MONEY>1.8817 marks</MONEY>, down from <MONEY>1.9120 marks</MONEY> <DATE>Tuesday</DATE>, and at <MONEY>133.86 yen</MONEY>, down from <MONEY>134.13 yen</MONEY>. 
In <LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION> on <DATE>Thursday</DATE>, the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> currency opened at <MONEY>133.93 yen</MONEY>. 
In <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> on <DATE>Wednesday</DATE>, the pound rose to <MONEY>$1.6865</MONEY>, from <MONEY>$1.6745</MONEY> <DATE>Tuesday</DATE>. 

   <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> short-term market interest rates on average are more than three percentage points higher than West German rates, making the higher-yielding dollar more attractive to foreign investors. 
Boosting West German rates would narrow the gap and help take pressure off of the mark, economists say. 

   The bulk of the dollar's decline yesterday reflected renewed mark strength as opposed to heightened dollar pessimism, dealers said. 
"Most of the action. . .was in mark-sterling, followed closely by mark-yen," said <PERSON>Peter Van der Mespel</PERSON>, corporate foreign-exchange chief at <ORGANIZATION>Deutsche Genossenschaftsbank</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>. 

   "The latest West German trade figures showed just how undervalued the mark is right now," he said. 
"The <ORGANIZATION>Bundesbank</ORGANIZATION> surely is growing weary of spending so many dollars propping up its currency, and the trade figures might provide them with the perfect excuse to raise interest rates instead." 

   Preliminary figures, confirmed yesterday, showed <LOCATION>West Germany</LOCATION>'s trade surplus surged <PERCENT>38%</PERCENT> in <DATE>June</DATE> to a record <MONEY>14.2 billion marks</MONEY> (<MONEY>$7.44 billion</MONEY>) from <MONEY>10.3 billion marks</MONEY> in <DATE>May</DATE>. 

   Dealers also said a late mark rally was triggered by a large stop-loss order from a <LOCATION>London</LOCATION> clearing-house bank to sell sterling for marks when the pound fell to <MONEY>3.1775 marks</MONEY>. 
One <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> dealer estimated the order totaled between <MONEY>#250 million</MONEY> (<MONEY>$418.8 million</MONEY>) and <MONEY>#500 million</MONEY>, "more than enough to move the market." 

   The pound, which dropped to an intraday low of around <MONEY>3.1500 marks</MONEY> before recovering to trade near <MONEY>3.1740 marks</MONEY>, is under pressure as the foreign-exchange market braces itself for today's announcement of poor <LOCATION>U.K.</LOCATION> trade data. 

   Economists expect a British trade deficit of <MONEY>#1.3 billion</MONEY> to <MONEY>#1.7 billion</MONEY>, widened from <DATE>June</DATE>'s <MONEY>#1 billion</MONEY> shortfall. 
Some dealers say the <LOCATION>U.K.</LOCATION> trade data to some extent may determine what, if any, interest-rate action the <ORGANIZATION>Bundesbank</ORGANIZATION> takes at its meeting today. 

   "With so much trading focused on pound-mark cross trading, the <LOCATION>U.K.</LOCATION> trade figures will be crucial," said mark trader <PERSON>Jerry Eagan</PERSON> at the <ORGANIZATION>Bank of Boston</ORGANIZATION>. 
"The <ORGANIZATION>Bank of England</ORGANIZATION> might even choose to raise its own interest rates if the trade figures cause the pound to fall dramatically, and that would present an entirely new set of circumstances to the <ORGANIZATION>Bundesbank</ORGANIZATION> officials." 

   On <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION>Commodity Exchange</ORGANIZATION>, gold for current delivery settled at <MONEY>$434.90</MONEY> an ounce, up <MONEY>$2.70</MONEY>. 
Estimated volume was a light to moderate 2.6 million ounces. 

   In <LOCATION>Hong Kong</LOCATION> <DATE>early Thursday</DATE>, gold was quoted at <MONEY>$434.25</MONEY> an ounce. 

