<HL> Currency Markets:
Dollar's Rise
Is Cut in Move
By 2 Nations
---
Sales by Fed, Bundesbank
Follow a 7-Month High
For Unit in Frankfurt
---
By Charles W. Stevens
Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal</HL>
<DD> 08/07/87</DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO>
<IN> EUROP CANDA FREST JAPAN
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
FOREIGN-EXCHANGE MARKETS (FRX)
PRECIOUS METALS, STONES, GOLD, SILVER (PCS)
COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD) </IN>
<TEXT>
   For the third consecutive day, some major central banks fought off a bullish charge by the dollar, substantially limiting the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> currency's gains. 

   The intervention by the <ORGANIZATION>U.S. Federal Reserve</ORGANIZATION> and the West German <ORGANIZATION>Bundesbank</ORGANIZATION> seemed to represent a stepped-up effort to contain the dollar in its surge prompted by fears of a widened <LOCATION>Persian Gulf</LOCATION> war. 
Yesterday's action appeared more coordinated than the earlier efforts. 

   As before, all central bank dollar sales were against the West German mark. 
However, in late <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> trading the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> currency still held part of its advance for the day, standing at <MONEY>1.8836 marks</MONEY>, compared with 1.8804 late <DATE>Wednesday</DATE>. 

   "The (intervention) had a very short-term effect in the market," a trader at a commercial bank that deals with the <ORGANIZATION>Fed</ORGANIZATION> said. 
Commercial bank traders with firsthand knowledge of the intervention estimated that the <ORGANIZATION>Fed</ORGANIZATION> sold <MONEY>$100 million</MONEY> through several banks in early <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> trading, shortly after the <ORGANIZATION>Bundesbank</ORGANIZATION> sold a like amount in the open market in <LOCATION>Frankfurt</LOCATION>. 

   The central banks formed a skirmish line for the dollar at <MONEY>1.8840 marks</MONEY>, where they sold the currency, knowledgeable traders said. 
Before its open-market intervention, the <ORGANIZATION>Bundesbank</ORGANIZATION> sold <MONEY>$5.7 million</MONEY> at yesterday's <LOCATION>Frankfurt</LOCATION> foreign exchange fixing as the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> currency rose to <MONEY>1.8842 marks</MONEY>, a seven-month high. 

   Traders say the intervention level stems from <DATE>February</DATE>'s <LOCATION>Louvre</LOCATION> accord in <LOCATION>Paris</LOCATION>. 
At that time, the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> and its major allies agreed to maintain exchange-rate stability, though they have never formally acknowledged setting specific target zones for rates. 

   There also was speculation that the <ORGANIZATION>Bank of England</ORGANIZATION> sold <MONEY>$100 million</MONEY> for marks in <LOCATION>London</LOCATION> trading. 

   But although the amounts represented an increase from the level of intervention reported early this week, the activity was still modest compared with the central banks' coordinated effort to support the dollar this <DATE>spring</DATE>. 
For this reason, some traders say the central banks now seek only to check the dollar's advance, not to reverse it. 

   "If the central banks really wanted to turn the market around, to get us back to 1.80 (marks), they'd come in with heavy dollars," <PERSON>Valerie J. Walker</PERSON>, vice president, foreign exchange, at <ORGANIZATION>Harris Trust &amp; Savings Bank</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>, said. 
"They just don't want the dollar to go breakneck to 1.90 without there being some fundamental justification." 

   In other trading, the British pound eased to <MONEY>$1.5773</MONEY> from <MONEY>$1.5797</MONEY> despite an increase of a full percentage point, to <PERCENT>10%</PERCENT>, in the base lending rate of some major British banks. 
The move followed the <ORGANIZATION>Bank of England</ORGANIZATION>'s action in raising its money market intervention rate a full point to <PERCENT>9 7/8%</PERCENT>. 

   Higher British interest rates should make sterling-denominated investments more attractive and increase demand for the pound. 
But traders interpreted yesterday's rate increase as a government-inspired move to control inflation, and inflationary fears have put sterling under pressure in recent weeks. 

   "Raising the rates scared people as to the actual state of the economy," <PERSON>Anthony J. Murphy</PERSON>, a sterling trader for <ORGANIZATION>Royal Bank of Canada</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>, said. 

   The dollar was slightly higher on the day against most other major currencies as well, rising to 151.45 Japanese yen in late <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> trading from 150.82 a day earlier. 

   In early trading in <LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION> today, the dollar was quoted at <MONEY>151.20 yen</MONEY>. 

   On the <ORGANIZATION>Commodity Exchange</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>, gold for current delivery rose <MONEY>$1.20</MONEY> an ounce to <MONEY>$468</MONEY> in moderate trading. 
Estimated volume was 3.5 million ounces. 

   Gold was quoted at <MONEY>$468.45</MONEY> an ounce in early trading <DATE>today</DATE> in <LOCATION>Hong Kong</LOCATION>. 

