<HL> Currency Markets: Dollar's Rally Seen Signaling Further Gains --- Short-Term Strengthening Is Predicted as Currency Resists Selling Pressure </HL>
<AUTHOR> Peter Greiff (WSJ Staff) </AUTHOR>
<SO> </SO>
<CO> EUROP JAPAN CANDA FREST </CO>
<IN> MON PCS FRX CMD </IN>
<TEXT>
   A mild rally in the dollar <DATE>Friday</DATE> ended two weeks of lethargic trading and stirred speculation that the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> currency will strengthen in the short run. 

   The speculation is largely based on charts of recent trading activity and observations that despite widespread bearish sentiment, selling pressure hasn't been enough to push the dollar sharply lower. 

   "The momentum, or lack of it, has been a little frustrating on the downside," said <PERSON>Teri Reid</PERSON>, a corporate foreign exchange adviser at <ORGANIZATION>Harris Trust &amp; Savings Bank</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>Chicago</LOCATION>. 
"There's more of a likelihood to test the upside," she said. 

   A spate of positive economic news combined with technical factors to push the dollar higher against continental European currencies and the yen <DATE>Friday</DATE>. 

   The pound, meanwhile, climbed on news that the British trade deficit for <DATE>March</DATE> was much narrower than expected. 
Sterling later surrendered most of its gains. 
Dealers reported that the <ORGANIZATION>Bank of England</ORGANIZATION> intervened to smooth the pound's rise as it hit an intraday high of <MONEY>$1.8850</MONEY>. 

   In late <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> trading, the dollar stood at <MONEY>1.6775 West German marks</MONEY>, up from 1.6698 <DATE>Thursday</DATE>. 
The dollar also climbed to <MONEY>125.18 yen</MONEY>, from 124.52. 
The pound rose to <MONEY>$1.8765</MONEY>, from <MONEY>$1.8729</MONEY>. 

   In midmorning trading in <LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION> <DATE>Monday</DATE>, the dollar was quoted at <MONEY>125.28 yen</MONEY>. 

   The dollar benefited from a series of economic reports <DATE>Friday</DATE> and firming interest rates, dealers said. 
Traders also bought dollars to square short, or oversold, positions in the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> currency before an expected liquidity drain in the markets this week caused by holidays in <LOCATION>Europe</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>. 

   It was reported <DATE>Friday</DATE> that the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> index of leading economic indicators for <DATE>March</DATE> rose <PERCENT>0.8%</PERCENT>, a little more than expected, while the <DATE>February</DATE> index was revised to a <PERCENT>1.3%</PERCENT> increase from the previously reported <PERCENT>0.9%</PERCENT> rise. 
Also, <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> new single-family home sales were reported to have risen <PERCENT>4%</PERCENT> in <DATE>March</DATE>. 
And a small <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> bank, <ORGANIZATION>Riggs National Bank</ORGANIZATION>, raised its prime lending rate to <PERCENT>8 3/4%</PERCENT> from <PERCENT>8 1/2%</PERCENT>. 

   The mildly stronger dollar set off talk among dealers that a rising <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> currency may reach significant chart points next week, but none said he expects to see a break beyond <MONEY>127 yen</MONEY>. 

   <PERSON>Victor Von Klemperer</PERSON>, manager of foreign exchange at <ORGANIZATION>BankAmerica International</ORGANIZATION>, said some significant stop-loss buying could be triggered if the dollar continues its upward drift. 
"If we break through some stops, not too far from where we are now, we could be heading for new highs" compared with levels of the past two weeks, he said. 

   Against the backdrop of the dollar's stagnant behavior recently, <PERSON>Ms. Reid</PERSON> at <ORGANIZATION>Harris Trust</ORGANIZATION> said <DATE>Friday</DATE>'s trading could have shown some short-term buying momentum. 
"There seemed to have been a little more interest and activity when the dollar was trading up" <DATE>Friday</DATE>, she said. 

   On the <ORGANIZATION>Commodity Exchange</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>, gold for current delivery rose <MONEY>40 cents</MONEY> an ounce to <MONEY>$451</MONEY> in light trading. 
The estimated volume was 1.8 million ounces. 

   In <LOCATION>Hong Kong</LOCATION>, gold was quoted at <MONEY>$450.70</MONEY> an ounce in early trading. 

