<HL> Currency Markets:
Dollar Declines
Amid Rumors
Of U.S. Selling
---
Unconfirmed Word of Move
By Fed Follows Rally
Based on Economic Data
---
By Charles W. Stevens
Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal</HL>
<DD> 07/31/87</DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO>
<IN> EUROP CANDA FREST JAPAN
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
PRECIOUS METALS, STONES, GOLD, SILVER (PCS)
COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD)
FOREIGN-EXCHANGE MARKETS (FRX) </IN>
<TEXT>
   A rumor of central bank selling of dollars snapped the foreign exchange market out of a <DATE>summer</DATE> lull, stifling a modest rally in the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> currency and leaving the dollar a little lower for the day. 

   The British pound also took a beating in the market, prompting the <ORGANIZATION>Bank of England</ORGANIZATION> to come to its rescue by buying sterling in the open market, traders said. 

   Although activity was sudden and hectic, the swing in exchange rates wasn't large by current market standards. 
Still, the moves caught many dealers by surprise in a market that had been marked by several days of slow <DATE>summer</DATE> trading. 

   The dollar moved to an intraday high of 1.8625 West German marks in morning <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> trading after the <ORGANIZATION>Commerce Department</ORGANIZATION> said <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> leading economic indicators rose a better-than-expected <PERCENT>0.8%</PERCENT> last month. 

   But just as traders began loading up on dollars in response to the report, rumors raced through the market that the <ORGANIZATION>U.S. Federal Reserve Bank</ORGANIZATION> had sold dollars to cut off the currency's rise. 

   Simultaneously, rumors surfaced that the West German central bank, the <ORGANIZATION>Bundesbank</ORGANIZATION>, either sold dollars or had placed orders to sell the dollar if it rose to <MONEY>1.8650 marks</MONEY>. 
Although none of the speculation was confirmed, the rumors themselves prevented the dollar from reaching that level. 

   Little more than an hour after reaching its intraday high, the dollar had fallen <PERCENT>0.5%</PERCENT> to its low for the day of <MONEY>1.8535 marks</MONEY>. 

   "There was a very choppy, panicky selling," <PERSON>Betsy Hoy</PERSON>, a corporate trader at <ORGANIZATION>Chemical Bank</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>, said. 
"It was a scary market. 
The market was glutted with dollars right away." 

   Although the dollar sell-off originated in trading against the mark, the currency ended up falling farther against the Japanese yen. 
In late <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> trading, it stood at <MONEY>149.51 yen</MONEY>, down <PERCENT>0.8%</PERCENT> from 150.75 late <DATE>Wednesday</DATE>. 
Against the mark, by contrast, it eventually firmed to stand at <MONEY>1.8550 marks</MONEY>, only <PERCENT>0.2%</PERCENT> lower than 1.8580 a day earlier. 

   The dollar was quoted at <MONEY>149.60 yen</MONEY> in early <LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION> trading today. 

   Meanwhile, the pound came under pressure from heavy corporate selling in <LOCATION>London</LOCATION>, traders said, prompting <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION>'s central bank to buy the currency. 
After reaching an intraday low of <MONEY>$1.5888</MONEY>, the pound climbed back to stand at <MONEY>$1.5930</MONEY>, still down from <MONEY>$1.5995</MONEY> a day earlier. 

   The pound fell farther against the West German currency, to <MONEY>2.9550 marks</MONEY> from 2.9719. 

   The rumors of central bank intervention revived speculation among currency traders that the major industrial nations are maintaining a secret target zone for exchange rates. 
The speculation first surfaced this <DATE>spring</DATE> when central banks of the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>West Germany</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>France</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> bought billions of dollars in the market to halt a major decline by the currency. 
Later, when a recovery took the dollar to around <MONEY>1.87 marks</MONEY>, traders said central banks sold the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> currency to halt its rise. 

   "The rumors of the central bank intervention really put a lid on the dollar. 
We may indeed be in a target zone," <PERSON>Albert Soria</PERSON>, vice president and foreign exchange manager for <ORGANIZATION>Swiss Bank Corp.</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>, said. 
"I think we'll continue trading in a very tight range," he said. 

   On the <ORGANIZATION>Commodity Exchange</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>, gold for current delivery rose <MONEY>$4.80</MONEY> an ounce to <MONEY>$462.20</MONEY> in heavy trading. 
Estimated volume was seven million ounces. 

