<HL> Currency Markets:
Dollar Shows
Little Change;
Talks Awaited
---
Traders See Unit Resuming
Its Fall After Meetings
Of Finance Officials End
---
By Charles W. Stevens
Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal</HL>
<DD> 04/08/87</DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO>
<IN> EUROP FREST CANDA JAPAN
FOREIGN-EXCHANGE MARKETS (FRX)
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
PRECIOUS METALS, STONES, GOLD, SILVER (PCS)
COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD) </IN>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was little changed in apprehensive trading as finance ministers from the major industrial nations prepared for meetings in <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION> today. 

   Comments by <ORGANIZATION>U.S. Federal Reserve Board</ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON>Paul Volcker</PERSON> on Capitol Hill inspired some dollar buying. 
But the currency's gains were limited by traders' long-term bearishness and the uncertainty over the <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION> meetings. 

   The finance ministers are in <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION> for the semiannual meeting of the <ORGANIZATION>International Monetary Fund</ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION>World Bank</ORGANIZATION>. 
Top finance officials from the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>West Germany</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>France</LOCATION> are expected to meet today for talks on currency rates, and they may be joined by their Canadian and Italian counterparts. 

   Many dealers predicted that no significant result will emerge from the meetings and that the dollar will resume its long decline next week. 

   "We're just biding time, waiting for something to break," <PERSON>Paul O. Steinborn</PERSON>, a foreign-exchange adviser at <ORGANIZATION>BankAmerica International</ORGANIZATION>, said. 
<LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> and other officials have indicated that the talks will produce a reaffirmation of the <DATE>Feb. 22</DATE> Paris accord, in which major industrial nations agreed to promote exchange-rate stability. 

   The absence of a significant agreement at this week's meetings would be a negative development for the dollar, <PERSON>Mr. Steinborn</PERSON> said. 
Other traders said that to avoid a resumed dollar sell-off next week, the finance ministers must at least reaffirm their <DATE>February</DATE> agreement. 

   What little action there was in the foreign-exchange market yesterday followed <PERSON>Mr. Volcker</PERSON>'s remarks to a <ORGANIZATION>Senate Banking Committee</ORGANIZATION> panel. 
The <ORGANIZATION>Fed</ORGANIZATION> chairman warned of "clear dangers" in relying too much on exchange-rate changes to shrink the huge <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> trade deficit, and he cited a possible resurgence in inflation. 
<PERSON>Mr. Volcker</PERSON> also said exchange-rate volatility could erode confidence in the stability of financial markets and could worsen Third World debt problems. 

   "He took the dollar a little bit higher, as he usually does," <PERSON>Samuel F. Lek</PERSON>, a trader at Bear, <ORGANIZATION>Stearns &amp; Co.</ORGANIZATION>, said of <PERSON>Mr. Volcker</PERSON>'s comments. 
"Nobody is going to sell dollars right while he's talking." 

   In late <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> trading yesterday, the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> currency stood at <MONEY>1.8275 West German marks</MONEY>, a slight advance from 1.8258 <DATE>Monday</DATE>. 
Against the Japanese currency, the dollar slipped to <MONEY>145.60 yen</MONEY> from 145.93. 
The British pound was marginally lower at <MONEY>$1.6180</MONEY>, compared with <MONEY>$1.6183</MONEY>. 

   In early <LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION> trading <DATE>Wednesday</DATE>, the dollar fell to <MONEY>145.33 yen</MONEY>. 

   On the <ORGANIZATION>Commodity Exchange</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>, gold for <DATE>April</DATE> delivery climbed <MONEY>$3.70</MONEY> an ounce to <MONEY>$422.20</MONEY> in moderate trading estimated at 2.8 million ounces. 

   Gold was quoted at <MONEY>$423</MONEY> an ounce in early trading <DATE>Wednesday</DATE> in <LOCATION>Hong Kong</LOCATION>. 

